{"title_page": "Colby Cave", "text_new": "{{short description|Canadian professional ice hockey player|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=October 2018}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox ice hockey player\n| name = Colby Cave\n| image = Colby Cave.jpg\n| image_size = 230px\n| caption = Cave with the [[Providence Bruins]] in 2015\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1994|12|26}}\n| birth_place = [[North Battleford, Saskatchewan]], Canada\n| death_date = {{death date and age|2020|04|11|1994|12|26}}\n| death_place = [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], [[Canada]]\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 1 <!-- Reference for height, unsure where to put <ref>{{cite web |last1=Umbach |first1=Jamie |title=ROSTER REBOOT: Colby Cave |url=https://www.nhl.com/oilers/news/roster-reboot-colby-cave/c-308648100 |website=NHL.com |accessdate=April 12, 2020 |date=August 23, 2019}}</ref> -->\n| weight_lbs = 201\n| position = [[Centre (ice hockey)|Centre]]\n| shoots = Left\n| played_for = [[Boston Bruins]]<br>[[Edmonton Oilers]]\n| ntl_team =\n| draft = Undrafted\n| career_start = 2015\n| career_end = 2020\n}}\n'''Colby Cave''' (December 26, 1994&nbsp;\u2013 April 11, 2020) was a [[Canadians|Canadian]] professional [[ice hockey]] [[Centre (ice hockey)|centre]] who played 67 games for the [[Boston Bruins]] and [[Edmonton Oilers]] of the [[National Hockey League]] (NHL) between 2017 and 2020. He also played several seasons with their respective affiliates in the [[American Hockey League]], the [[Providence Bruins]] and [[Bakersfield Condors]]. Prior to turning professional in 2015 Cave played [[major junior]] with the [[Swift Current Broncos]] of the [[Western Hockey League]].\n\n==Playing career==\n===Junior===\nCave was born in [[North Battleford, Saskatchewan]], but grew up in the town of [[Battleford, Saskatchewan]], and first played locally with the Battlefords Stars in the [[Saskatchewan Midget AAA Hockey League]] from 2009 to 2011. He was drafted to the major junior level with the 13th selection in the 2009 [[WHL Bantam Draft]] in 2009 by the [[Kootenay Ice]].<ref>{{cite web |title=ICE SELECT FORWARD IN FIRST ROUND |url=http://kootenayice.net/ice-select-forward-in-first-round |website=kootenayice.net |accessdate=October 30, 2018 |date=May 2, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181031005400/http://kootenayice.net/ice-select-forward-in-first-round |archive-date=October 31, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Cave's rights were later traded by Kootenay to the [[Swift Current Broncos]] on January 9, 2011.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://whl.ca/article/broncos-move-eakin-to-kootenay | title = Broncos move Eakin to Kootenay | publisher = [[Western Hockey League]] | date = January 9, 2011 | accessdate = January 9, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn his third full season with the Broncos, Cave was named team captain.<ref>{{cite web |title=Broncos Name Cave Captain |url=http://scbroncos.com/broncos-name-cave-captain/ |website=scbroncos.com |accessdate=October 30, 2018 |date=September 26, 2013}}</ref> He continued his development by elevating his offensive game to almost a point-per-game pace finishing with 70 points in 72 games. Eligible for the [[2014 NHL Entry Draft]], Cave was listed 157th overall by ISS Hockey, however, he was passed over. At the conclusion of his final junior season, placing second on the club in points with 75 in 72 games, Cave was signed as an undrafted free agent to a three-year, entry level contract by the [[Boston Bruins]] on April 4, 2015.<ref>{{cite web| url = https://www.nhl.com/bruins/news/bruins-sign-colby-cave-to-an-entry-level-contract/c-761863 | title = Bruins sign Colby Cave to entry-level contract | publisher = [[Boston Bruins]] | date = April 4, 2015 | accessdate = April 4, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Professional===\nCave spent most of the first three years of his professional career with the [[Providence Bruins]], the [[American Hockey League]] affiliate of the Bruins.<ref name=CBC/> During the final season of his rookie contract with the Bruins in [[2017\u201318 NHL season|2017\u201318]], Cave received his first recall to the NHL on an emergency basis by the Bruins on December 21, 2017.<ref>{{cite web| url = https://www.nhl.com/bruins/news/bruins-recall-colby-cave-on-emergency-basis/c-294254638 | title = Bruins recall Colby Cave on an emergency basis | publisher = [[Boston Bruins]] | date = December 21, 2017 | accessdate = December 21, 2017}}</ref> He made his NHL debut, playing alongside line-mate and former Broncos junior teammate, [[Jake DeBrusk]], in a 2\u20131 shootout victory over the [[Winnipeg Jets]]. He was then returned to Providence following the game.<ref>{{cite news| url = http://www.providencejournal.com/sports/20171221/colby-cave-with-old-friend-on-his-line-makes-nhl-debut | title = Colby Cave, with old friend on his line, makes NHL debut | newspaper = [[Providence Journal]] | date = December 22, 2017 | accessdate = December 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\nFollowing another call-up by the Boston team in the [[2018\u201319 NHL season|2018\u201319 season]], on December 17, 2018, Cave scored his first NHL career goal in a 4\u20130 shutout of the [[Montreal Canadiens]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nhl.com/news/boston-bruins-montreal-canadiens-game-recap/c-303029692 |title=Halak makes 22 saves, Bruins shut out Canadiens |last=Farrell |first=Sean |date=December 17, 2018 |website=nhl.com |publisher=National Hockey League |access-date=December 17, 2018 |quote=Colby Cave scored his first NHL goal and had an assist...}}</ref> He remained with Boston to appear in 20 games, posting 1 goal and 5 points, before he was placed on waivers by the Bruins for re-assignment to the [[American Hockey League]] (AHL). On January 15, 2019, Cave left the Bruins organization after he was claimed by the [[Edmonton Oilers]].<ref>{{cite web| url = https://www.nhl.com/oilers/news/blog-oilers-claim-colby-cave-from-boston/c-303911756?tid=281885062 | title = Oilers claim Colby Cave from Boston | publisher = [[Edmonton Oilers]] | date = January 15, 2019 | accessdate = January 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nCave suffered a [[Intracerebral hemorrhage|brain bleed]] due to a [[colloid cyst]] overnight on April 6\u20137, 2020, and underwent emergency surgery on April 7. He died after being in a [[medically induced coma]] in the early hours of April 11, at [[Sunnybrook Hospital]] in [[Toronto]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Oilers' Cave has surgery, remains in coma |url=https://www.tsn.ca/edmonton-oilers-f-colby-cave-in-coma-with-brain-bleed-1.1464043 |website=TSN.ca |accessdate=April 11, 2020 |date=April 7, 2020}}</ref><ref name=CBC>{{cite web |title=Oilers forward Colby Cave dies after suffering brain bleed |url=https://www.cbc.ca/sports/hockey/nhl/edmonton-oilers-colby-cave-1.5529808 |website=CBC.ca |accessdate=April 11, 2020 |date=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{| border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"text-align:center; width:60em\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n! colspan=\"3\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\"|\n! rowspan=\"100\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\"|\n! colspan=\"5\"|[[Regular season]]\n! rowspan=\"100\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\"|\n! colspan=\"5\"|[[Playoffs]]\n|- bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n! [[Season (sports)|Season]]\n! Team\n! League\n! GP !! [[Goal (ice hockey)|G]] !! [[Assist (ice hockey)|A]] !! [[Point (ice hockey)|Pts]] !! [[Penalty (ice hockey)|PIM]]\n! GP !! G !! A !! Pts !! PIM\n|-\n| 2008\u201309\n| Battlefords Stars\n| [[Saskatchewan Midget AAA Hockey League|SMHL]]\n| 3 || 0 || 1 || 1 || 2\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| 2009\u201310\n| Battlefords Stars\n| SMHL\n| 42 || 15 || 21 || 36 || 40\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|-\n| 2010\u201311\n| Battlefords Stars\n| SMHL\n| 44 || 14 || 22 || 36 || 28\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| 2010\u201311\n| [[Battlefords North Stars]]\n| [[Saskatchewan Junior Hockey League|SJHL]]\n| 3 || 0 || 1 || 1 || 0\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|-\n| [[2010\u201311 WHL season|2010\u201311]]\n| [[Swift Current Broncos]]\n| [[Western Hockey League|WHL]]\n| 1 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[2011\u201312 WHL season|2011\u201312]]\n| Swift Current Broncos\n| WHL\n| 70 || 6 || 10 || 16 || 36\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|-\n| [[2012\u201313 WHL season|2012\u201313]]\n| Swift Current Broncos\n| WHL\n| 72 || 21 || 20 || 41 || 39\n| 5 || 2 || 2 || 4 || 8\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[2013\u201314 WHL season|2013\u201314]]\n| Swift Current Broncos\n| WHL\n| 72 || 33 || 37 || 70 || 30\n| 6 || 0 || 2 || 2 || 0\n|-\n| [[2014\u201315 WHL season|2014\u201315]]\n| Swift Current Broncos\n| WHL\n| 72 || 35 || 40 || 75 || 52\n| 4 || 2 || 0 || 2 || 2\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[2014\u201315 AHL season|2014\u201315]]\n| [[Providence Bruins]]\n| [[American Hockey League|AHL]]\n| 1 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|-\n| [[2015\u201316 AHL season|2015\u201316]]\n| Providence Bruins\n| AHL\n| 75 || 13 || 16 || 29 || 27\n| 3 || 2 || 1 || 3 || 5\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[2016\u201317 AHL season|2016\u201317]]\n| Providence Bruins\n| AHL\n| 76 || 13 || 22 || 35 || 52\n| 17 || 1 || 5 || 6 || 18\n|-\n| [[2017\u201318 AHL season|2017\u201318]]\n| Providence Bruins\n| AHL\n| 72 || 11 || 22 || 33 || 29\n| 4 ||0 || 0 || 0 || 2\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[2017\u201318 NHL season|2017\u201318]]\n| [[Boston Bruins]]\n| [[National Hockey League|NHL]]\n| 3 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 2\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|-\n| [[2018\u201319 AHL season|2018\u201319]]\n| Providence Bruins\n| AHL\n| 15 || 6 || 12 || 18 || 13\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[2018\u201319 NHL season|2018\u201319]]\n| Boston Bruins\n| NHL\n| 20 || 1 || 4 || 5 || 8\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|-\n| 2018\u201319\n| [[Edmonton Oilers]]\n| NHL\n| 33 || 2 || 1 || 3 || 8\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[2019\u201320 NHL season|2019\u201320]]\n| Edmonton Oilers\n| NHL\n| 11 || 1 || 0 || 1 || 4\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|-\n| [[2019\u201320 AHL season|2019\u201320]]\n| [[Bakersfield Condors]]\n| AHL\n| 44 || 11 || 12 || 23 || 24\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|- bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n! colspan=\"3\"|NHL totals\n! 67 !! 4 !! 5 !! 9 !! 22\n! \u2014 !! \u2014 !! \u2014 !! \u2014 !! \u2014\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of ice hockey players who died during their playing career]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Ice hockey stats|nhl=8477529|elite=84424|hockeydb=132916}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cave, Colby}}\n[[Category:1994 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Bakersfield Condors players]]\n[[Category:Boston Bruins players]]\n[[Category:Canadian expatriate ice hockey players in the United States]]\n[[Category:Canadian ice hockey centres]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cerebrovascular disease]]\n[[Category:Edmonton Oilers players]]\n[[Category:Ice hockey people from Saskatchewan]]\n[[Category:People from Battleford]]\n[[Category:Providence Bruins players]]\n[[Category:Swift Current Broncos players]]\n[[Category:Undrafted National Hockey League players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Canadian professional ice hockey player|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=October 2018}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox ice hockey player\n| name = Colby Cave\n| image = Colby Cave.jpg\n| image_size = 230px\n| caption = Cave with the [[Providence Bruins]] in 2015\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1994|12|26}}\n| birth_place = [[North Battleford, Saskatchewan]], Canada\n| death_date = {{death date and age|2020|04|11|1994|12|26}}\n| death_place = [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], [[Canada]]\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 1 <!-- Reference for height, unsure where to put <ref>{{cite web |last1=Umbach |first1=Jamie |title=ROSTER REBOOT: Colby Cave |url=https://www.nhl.com/oilers/news/roster-reboot-colby-cave/c-308648100 |website=NHL.com |accessdate=April 12, 2020 |date=August 23, 2019}}</ref> -->\n| weight_lbs = 201\n| position = [[Centre (ice hockey)|Centre]]\n| shoots = Left\n| played_for = [[Boston Bruins]]<br>[[Edmonton Oilers]]\n| ntl_team =\n| draft = Undrafted\n| career_start = 2015\n| career_end = 2020\n}}\n'''Colby Cave''' (December 26, 1994 \u2013 April 11, 2020) was a [[Canadians|Canadian]] professional [[ice hockey]] [[Centre (ice hockey)|centre]] who played 67 games for the [[Boston Bruins]] and [[Edmonton Oilers]] of the [[National Hockey League]] (NHL) between 2017 and 2020. He also played several seasons with their respective affiliates in the [[American Hockey League]], the [[Providence Bruins]] and [[Bakersfield Condors]]. Prior to turning professional in 2015 Cave played [[major junior]] with the [[Swift Current Broncos]] of the [[Western Hockey League]].\n\n==Playing career==\n===Junior===\nCave was born in [[North Battleford, Saskatchewan]], but grew up in the town of [[Battleford, Saskatchewan]], and first played locally with the Battlefords Stars in the [[Saskatchewan Midget AAA Hockey League]] from 2009 to 2011. He was drafted to the major junior level with the 13th selection in the 2009 [[WHL Bantam Draft]] in 2009 by the [[Kootenay Ice]].<ref>{{cite web |title=ICE SELECT FORWARD IN FIRST ROUND |url=http://kootenayice.net/ice-select-forward-in-first-round |website=kootenayice.net |accessdate=October 30, 2018 |date=May 2, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181031005400/http://kootenayice.net/ice-select-forward-in-first-round |archive-date=October 31, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Cave's rights were later traded by Kootenay to the [[Swift Current Broncos]] on January 9, 2011.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://whl.ca/article/broncos-move-eakin-to-kootenay | title = Broncos move Eakin to Kootenay | publisher = [[Western Hockey League]] | date = January 9, 2011 | accessdate = January 9, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn his third full season with the Broncos, Cave was named team captain.<ref>{{cite web |title=Broncos Name Cave Captain |url=http://scbroncos.com/broncos-name-cave-captain/ |website=scbroncos.com |accessdate=October 30, 2018 |date=September 26, 2013}}</ref> He continued his development by elevating his offensive game to almost a point-per-game pace finishing with 70 points in 72 games. Eligible for the [[2014 NHL Entry Draft]], Cave was listed 157th overall by ISS Hockey, however, he was passed over. At the conclusion of his final junior season, placing second on the club in points with 75 in 72 games, Cave was signed as an undrafted free agent to a three-year, entry level contract by the [[Boston Bruins]] on April 4, 2015.<ref>{{cite web| url = https://www.nhl.com/bruins/news/bruins-sign-colby-cave-to-an-entry-level-contract/c-761863 | title = Bruins sign Colby Cave to entry-level contract | publisher = [[Boston Bruins]] | date = April 4, 2015 | accessdate = April 4, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Professional===\nCave spent most of the first three years of his professional career with the [[Providence Bruins]], the [[American Hockey League]] affiliate of the Bruins.<ref name=CBC/> During the final season of his rookie contract with the Bruins in [[2017\u201318 NHL season|2017\u201318]], Cave received his first recall to the NHL on an emergency basis by the Bruins on December 21, 2017.<ref>{{cite web| url = https://www.nhl.com/bruins/news/bruins-recall-colby-cave-on-emergency-basis/c-294254638 | title = Bruins recall Colby Cave on an emergency basis | publisher = [[Boston Bruins]] | date = December 21, 2017 | accessdate = December 21, 2017}}</ref> He made his NHL debut, playing alongside line-mate and former Broncos junior teammate, [[Jake DeBrusk]], in a 2\u20131 shootout victory over the [[Winnipeg Jets]]. He was then returned to Providence following the game.<ref>{{cite news| url = http://www.providencejournal.com/sports/20171221/colby-cave-with-old-friend-on-his-line-makes-nhl-debut | title = Colby Cave, with old friend on his line, makes NHL debut | newspaper = [[Providence Journal]] | date = December 22, 2017 | accessdate = December 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\nFollowing another call-up by the Boston team in the [[2018\u201319 NHL season|2018\u201319 season]], on December 17, 2018, Cave scored his first NHL career goal in a 4\u20130 shutout of the [[Montreal Canadiens]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nhl.com/news/boston-bruins-montreal-canadiens-game-recap/c-303029692 |title=Halak makes 22 saves, Bruins shut out Canadiens |last=Farrell |first=Sean |date=December 17, 2018 |website=nhl.com |publisher=National Hockey League |access-date=December 17, 2018 |quote=Colby Cave scored his first NHL goal and had an assist...}}</ref> He remained with Boston to appear in 20 games, posting 1 goal and 5 points, before he was placed on waivers by the Bruins for re-assignment to the [[American Hockey League]] (AHL). On January 15, 2019, Cave left the Bruins organization after he was claimed by the [[Edmonton Oilers]].<ref>{{cite web| url = https://www.nhl.com/oilers/news/blog-oilers-claim-colby-cave-from-boston/c-303911756?tid=281885062 | title = Oilers claim Colby Cave from Boston | publisher = [[Edmonton Oilers]] | date = January 15, 2019 | accessdate = January 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nCave suffered a [[Intracerebral hemorrhage|brain bleed]] due to a [[colloid cyst]] overnight on April 6\u20137, 2020, and underwent emergency surgery on April 7. He died after being in a [[medically induced coma]] in the early hours of April 11, at [[Sunnybrook Hospital]] in [[Toronto]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Oilers' Cave has surgery, remains in coma |url=https://www.tsn.ca/edmonton-oilers-f-colby-cave-in-coma-with-brain-bleed-1.1464043 |website=TSN.ca |accessdate=April 11, 2020 |date=April 7, 2020}}</ref><ref name=CBC>{{cite web |title=Oilers forward Colby Cave dies after suffering brain bleed |url=https://www.cbc.ca/sports/hockey/nhl/edmonton-oilers-colby-cave-1.5529808 |website=CBC.ca |accessdate=April 11, 2020 |date=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{| border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"text-align:center; width:60em\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n! colspan=\"3\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\"|\n! rowspan=\"100\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\"|\n! colspan=\"5\"|[[Regular season]]\n! rowspan=\"100\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\"|\n! colspan=\"5\"|[[Playoffs]]\n|- bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n! [[Season (sports)|Season]]\n! Team\n! League\n! GP !! [[Goal (ice hockey)|G]] !! [[Assist (ice hockey)|A]] !! [[Point (ice hockey)|Pts]] !! [[Penalty (ice hockey)|PIM]]\n! GP !! G !! A !! Pts !! PIM\n|-\n| 2008\u201309\n| Battlefords Stars\n| [[Saskatchewan Midget AAA Hockey League|SMHL]]\n| 3 || 0 || 1 || 1 || 2\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| 2009\u201310\n| Battlefords Stars\n| SMHL\n| 42 || 15 || 21 || 36 || 40\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|-\n| 2010\u201311\n| Battlefords Stars\n| SMHL\n| 44 || 14 || 22 || 36 || 28\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| 2010\u201311\n| [[Battlefords North Stars]]\n| [[Saskatchewan Junior Hockey League|SJHL]]\n| 3 || 0 || 1 || 1 || 0\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|-\n| [[2010\u201311 WHL season|2010\u201311]]\n| [[Swift Current Broncos]]\n| [[Western Hockey League|WHL]]\n| 1 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[2011\u201312 WHL season|2011\u201312]]\n| Swift Current Broncos\n| WHL\n| 70 || 6 || 10 || 16 || 36\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|-\n| [[2012\u201313 WHL season|2012\u201313]]\n| Swift Current Broncos\n| WHL\n| 72 || 21 || 20 || 41 || 39\n| 5 || 2 || 2 || 4 || 8\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[2013\u201314 WHL season|2013\u201314]]\n| Swift Current Broncos\n| WHL\n| 72 || 33 || 37 || 70 || 30\n| 6 || 0 || 2 || 2 || 0\n|-\n| [[2014\u201