{"title_page": "Constant Headache", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Constant Headache\n| cover      = \n| alt        =\n| border     = yes\n| type       = song\n| artist     = [[Joyce Manor]]\n| album      = [[Joyce Manor (album)|Joyce Manor]]\n| released   = {{Start date|2011|01|11|mf=yes}}\n| recorded   = \n| studio     =  \n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Indie rock]]|[[emo]]}}\n| length     = {{Duration|m=3|s=04}}\n| label      = 6131\n| writer     = \n*Barry Johnson\n*Matt Ebert\n*Chase Knobbe\n*Kurt Walcher\n| producer   = Alex Estrada\n}}\n\n\"'''Constant Headache'''\" is a song recorded by American rock band [[Joyce Manor]]. The song was released on January 11, 2011 as part of their [[Joyce Manor (album)|self-titled debut album]]. It was also the namesake of the group's extended play of the same name, first released a year prior. The song is generally considered the band's [[signature song]].<ref name=\"bb\">{{cite news|url=https://www.spin.com/featured/joyce-manor-cody-new-album-interview/|title=This Is Post-Growing Up: Joyce Manor's Story Gets Boring So Their Songs and Crowds Don't Have To|date=September 21, 2018|first=Andrew|last=Unterberger|work=Billboard|accessdate=March 6, 2020}}</ref> \n==Background==\nThe song was, like many tracks on the band's debut, developed over a period of many years.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kerrang.com/features/joyce-manor-album-by-album-with-barry-johnson/|title=JOYCE MANOR: ALBUM BY ALBUM WITH FRONTMAN BARRY JOHNSON|date=September 10, 2019|first= Danielle |last=Chelosky|work=Kerrang!|accessdate=March 6, 2020}}</ref> An early version of the song exists with an additional third verse, though Johnson has joked it would be too unusual to release, given fans' love of the original.<ref name=\"spin\"/> He has admitted in an interview that the song's melody was inspired by [[the Human League]]'s \"[[Don't You Want Me Baby]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lancasteronline.com/features/entertainment/joyce-manor-s-barry-johnson-on-short-songs-great-melodies/article_ed723e9e-ee19-11e6-b9c7-8b88fc8ef341.html|title=Joyce Manor's Barry Johnson on short songs, great melodies and growing up in pop-punk|date=February 8, 2017|first= Jenelle |last=Janci|work=[[LNP (newspaper)|LNP]]|accessdate=March 6, 2020}}</ref> Listeners have theorized that the song's lyrics were written from the perspective of a dog, though Johnson has expressed confusion at this: \"I can't pin down exactly which line it is that suggests that. Clearly, there's something there because it's too strange of a coincidence.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://columbiachronicle.com/e77233a8-c0ac-11e7-b791-1795bf6416b2|title=For Joyce Manor, pop-punk popularity hasn\u2019t been a \u2018Constant Headache\u2019|date=November 6, 2017|first= Tyra |last=Bosnic|work=[[The Columbia Chronicle]]|accessdate=March 6, 2020}}</ref>\n==Reception==\n\"Constant Headache\" rapidly became the band's most popular song, a frequent [[encore]] at their concerts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.spin.com/featured/joyce-manor-cody-new-album-interview/|title=Joyce Manor: These Things Take Time|date=September 1, 2016|first= Andrew |last=Unterberger|work=Spin|accessdate=March 6, 2020}}</ref> Johnson remembered in an interview that the lyrics of the song, combined with [[GIF]] images from the band's shows, spread on [[social media]] sites like [[Tumblr]], including early [[word-of-mouth]] for the act.<ref name=\"bb\"/> The song has been covered by [[Conor Oberst]]'s [[Desaparecidos (band)|Desaparecidos]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stereogum.com/featured/joyce-manor-million-dollars-to-kill-me-interview/|title=In The Garage: Joyce Manor Share The Scenes And Stories Behind Million Dollars To Kill Me|date=August 21, 2018|first=Ian|last=Cohen|website=Stereogum|accessdate=March 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nChris Payne at ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' considered it the album's \"biggest anthem,\" pointing out humorously that while the majority of its songs were fast and short, \"Constant Headache\" is the only song to stretch to three minutes.<ref name=\"bb1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6077614/top-10-new-school-pop-punk-bands-modern-baseball-candy-hearts|title=Top 10 New School Pop-Punk Bands You Need To Know|date=May 8, 2014|first=Chris|last=Payne|work=Billboard|accessdate=March 6, 2020}}</ref> ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' contributor Brad Nelson retrospectively dubbed it \"still their most enduring song, a knot of feeling shoved forward by its own chord progression, punk as temporary and awesome as a wave on beach.\"<ref name=\"spin\">{{cite web|url=https://www.spin.com/featured/joyce-manor-million-dollars-to-kill-me-interview/|title=Joyce Manor Is Excited to Be Bored|date=October 23, 2018|first=Brad|last=Nelson|work=Spin|accessdate=March 6, 2020}}</ref> Whitney Shoemaker of ''[[Alternative Press (magazine)|Alternative Press]]'' recalled it as one of the most distinctive emo songs of 2011.<ref name=\"ap\">{{cite web|url=https://www.altpress.com/features/top-50-emo-songs-2010s-decade/|title=Top 50 emo songs of the decade that defined the 2010s|date=October 23, 2018|first=Whitney|last=Shoemaker|work=Alternative Press|accessdate=March 6, 2020}}</ref>\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|joyce-manor|constant-headache}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n{{Template:Joyce Manor}}\n[[Category:2011 songs]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Constant Headache\n| cover      = \n| alt        =\n| border     = yes\n| type       = song\n| artist     = [[Joyce Manor]]\n| album      = [[Joyce Manor (album)|Joyce Manor]]\n| released   = {{Start date|2011|01|11|mf=yes}}\n| recorded   = \n| studio     =  \n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Indie rock]]|[[emo]]}}\n| length     = {{Duration|m=3|s=04}}\n| label      = 6131\n| writer     = \n*Barry Johnson\n*Matt Ebert\n*Chase Knobbe\n*Kurt Walcher\n| producer   = Alex Estrada\n}}\n\n\"'''Constant Headache'''\" is a song recorded by American rock band [[Joyce Manor]]. The song was released on January 11, 2011 as part of their [[Joyce Manor (album)|self-titled debut album]]. It was also the namesake of the group's extended play of the same name, first released a year prior. The song is generally considered the band's [[signature song]].<ref name=\"bb\">{{cite news|url=https://www.spin.com/featured/joyce-manor-cody-new-album-interview/|title=This Is Post-Growing Up: Joyce Manor's Story Gets Boring So Their Songs and Crowds Don't Have To|date=September 21, 2018|first=Andrew|last=Unterberger|work=Billboard|accessdate=March 6, 2020}}</ref> \n==Background==\nThe song was, like many tracks on the band's debut, developed over a period of many years.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kerrang.com/features/joyce-manor-album-by-album-with-barry-johnson/|title=JOYCE MANOR: ALBUM BY ALBUM WITH FRONTMAN BARRY JOHNSON|date=September 10, 2019|first= Danielle |last=Chelosky|work=Kerrang!|accessdate=March 6, 2020}}</ref> An early version of the song exists with an additional third verse, though Johnson has joked it would be too unusual to release, given fans' love of the original.<ref name=\"spin\"/> He has admitted in an interview that the song's melody was inspired by [[the Human League]]'s \"[[Don't You Want Me Baby]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lancasteronline.com/features/entertainment/joyce-manor-s-barry-johnson-on-short-songs-great-melodies/article_ed723e9e-ee19-11e6-b9c7-8b88fc8ef341.html|title=Joyce Manor's Barry Johnson on short songs, great melodies and growing up in pop-punk|date=February 8, 2017|first= Jenelle |last=Janci|work=[[LNP (newspaper)|LNP]]|accessdate=March 6, 2020}}</ref> Listeners have theorized that the song's lyrics were written from the perspective of a dog, though Johnson has expressed confusion at this: \"I can't pin down exactly which line it is that suggests that. Clearly, there's something there because it's too strange of a coincidence.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://columbiachronicle.com/e77233a8-c0ac-11e7-b791-1795bf6416b2|title=For Joyce Manor, pop-punk popularity hasn\u2019t been a \u2018Constant Headache\u2019|date=November 6, 2017|first= Tyra |last=Bosnic|work=[[The Columbia Chronicle]]|accessdate=March 6, 2020}}</ref>\n==Reception==\n\"Constant Headache\" rapidly became the band's most popular song, a frequent [[encore]] at their concerts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.spin.com/featured/joyce-manor-cody-new-album-interview/|title=Joyce Manor: These Things Take Time|date=September 1, 2016|first= Andrew |last=Unterberger|work=Spin|accessdate=March 6, 2020}}</ref> Johnson remembered in an interview that the lyrics of the song, combined with [[GIF]] images from the band's shows, spread on [[social media]] sites like [[Tumblr]], including early [[word-of-mouth]] for the act.<ref name=\"bb\"/> The song has been covered by [[Conor Oberst]]'s [[Desaparecidos (band)|Desaparecidos]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stereogum.com/featured/joyce-manor-million-dollars-to-kill-me-interview/|title=In The Garage: Joyce Manor Share The Scenes And Stories Behind Million Dollars To Kill Me|date=August 21, 2018|first=Ian|last=Cohen|website=Stereogum|accessdate=March 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nChris Payne at ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' considered it the album's \"biggest anthem,\" pointing out humorously that while the majority of its songs were fast and short, \"Constant Headache\" is the only song to stretch to three minutes.<ref name=\"bb1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6077614/top-10-new-school-pop-punk-bands-modern-baseball-candy-hearts|title=Top 10 New School Pop-Punk Bands You Need To Know|date=May 8, 2014|first=Chris|last=Payne|work=Billboard|accessdate=March 6, 2020}}</ref> ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' contributor Brad Nelson retrospectively dubbed it \"still their most enduring song, a knot of feeling shoved forward by its own chord progression, punk as temporary and awesome as a wave on beach.\"<ref name=\"spin\">{{cite web|url=https://www.spin.com/featured/joyce-manor-million-dollars-to-kill-me-interview/|title=Joyce Manor Is Excited to Be Bored|date=October 23, 2018|first=Brad|last=Nelson|work=Spin|accessdate=March 6, 2020}}</ref> Whitney Shoemaker of ''[[Alternative Press (magazine)|Alternative Press]]'' recalled it as one of the most distinctive emo songs of 2011.<ref name=\"ap\">{{cite web|url=https://www.altpress.com/features/top-50-emo-songs-2010s-decade/|title=Top 50 emo songs of the decade that defined the 2010s|date=October 23, 2018|first=Whitney|last=Shoemaker|work=Alternative Press|accessdate=March 6, 2020}}</ref>\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|joyce-manor|constant-headache}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n{{Template:Joyce Manor}}\n[[Category:2011 songs]]\n", "name_user": "Rfl0216", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Constant_Headache"}
