{"title_page": "Jamanxim Dam", "text_new": "{{Infobox dam\n| name                 = Jamanxim Dam\n| name_official        = Barragem Jardim Jamanxim\n| image                = \n| image_size           = 235\n| image_caption        = \n| image_alt            = \n| location_map         = Brazil\n| location_map_size    = \n| location_map_caption = \n| location_map_alt     = \n| coordinates          = {{coord|-5.658876|-55.874181|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n| country              = Brazil\n| location             = [[Itaituba]], Par\u00e1\n| purpose              = Hydroelectric\n| status               = Planned\n| construction_began   = \n| opening              = \n| demolished           = \n| cost                 = \n| owner                = \n| operator             = \n| dam_type             = \n| dam_crosses          = [[Jamanxim River]]\n| dam_height_foundation= \n| dam_height_thalweg   = {{convert|72|m}}\n| dam_length           = \n| dam_elevation_crest  = \n| dam_width_crest      = \n| dam_width_base       = \n| dam_volume           = \n| spillway_count       = \n| spillway_type        = \n| spillway_capacity    = \n| res_name             = \n| res_capacity_total   = \n| res_capacity_active  = \n| res_capacity_inactive= \n| res_catchment        = \n| res_surface          = {{convert|7400|ha}}\n| res_max_length       = \n| res_max_width        = \n| res_max_depth        = \n| res_elevation        = \n| res_tidal_range      = \n| plant_name           = \n| plant_coordinates    = \n| plant_operator       = \n| plant_commission     = \n| plant_decommission   = \n| plant_type           = \n| plant_hydraulic_head = \n| plant_turbines       = 3 [[Francis turbine]]s\n| plant_capacity       = {{convert|881|MW}}\n| plant_capacity_factor= \n| plant_annual_gen     = \n| website              = \n| extra                = \n}}\nThe '''Jamanxim Dam''' ({{lang-pt|Barragem Jamanxim}}) is a proposed hydroelectric dam on the [[Jamanxim River]] in the state of [[Par\u00e1]], Brazil.\n\n==Location==\n\nThe Jamanxim Dam is proposed to be built on the [[Jamanxim River]] in the state of Par\u00e1, in the [[Tapaj\u00f3s]] river basin.{{sfn|Jamanxim Perfil da usina}}\nIt would be built in the municipality of [[Itaituba]].\nThe dam would flood {{convert|8516|ha}} of the [[Jamanxim National Park]].\nIt would affect the [[South Amazon Ecotones Ecological Corridor]].{{sfn|Jamanxim Perfil da usina}}\n\nThe hydroelectric power plant will be part of the proposed {{convert|12,000|MW}} [[Tapaj\u00f3s hydroelectric complex]] on the Tapaj\u00f3s and Jamanxim rivers.{{sfn|Brazil sets concession auction for 8,040-MW Sao Luiz do Tapajos...}}\nOthers are the [[S\u00e3o Luiz do Tapaj\u00f3s Dam|S\u00e3o Luiz do Tapaj\u00f3s]] (6,133&nbsp;MW), [[Jatob\u00e1 Hydroelectric Power Plant|Jatob\u00e1]] (2,338&nbsp;MW), [[Cachoeira do Cai Dam|Cachoeira do Cai]] (802&nbsp;MW) and [[Cachoeira dos Patos Dam|Cachoeira dos Patos]] (528&nbsp;MW), all under study, as well as the [[Chacor\u00e3o Dam|Chacor\u00e3o]] (3,336&nbsp;MW) and [[Jardim do Ouro Dam|Jardim do Ouro]] (227&nbsp;MW).{{sfn|Jatob\u00e1 Perfil da usina \u2013Barragens na Amaz\u00f4nia}}\n\n==Technical==\n\nThe dam would be {{convert|72|m}} high, containing a reservoir with an area of {{convert|7445|ha}}.\nThe planned power plant would have potential of {{convert|881|MW}}, with guaranteed capacity of {{convert|475|MW}}.\nThe plant would contain 3 [[Francis turbine]]s, handling a flow of {{convert|1366|m3/s}}.{{sfn|Couto|2010}}\n\nEstimated cost would e US$984 million.\nThe project would be built by [[Eletrobras]], [[Eletronorte]], Constru\u00e7\u00f5es e Com\u00e9rcio Camargo C\u00f4rrea, EDF Consultoria em Projetos de Gera\u00e7\u00e3o de Energia, Endesa Brasil, EPP Energia El\u00e9trica, Promo\u00e7\u00e3o e Participa\u00e7\u00f5es, Neoenergia Investimentos and Odebrecht.{{sfn|Jamanxim Perfil da usina}}\n\n==Planning process==\n\nOn 20 January 2016 it was reported that the deadline for the feasibility study for the Jatob\u00e1 plant had been extended to December 2016, and the deadline for the Jamanxim plant feasibility study was now 31 December 2017.{{sfn|Prazo para entrega de estudos da UHE Jatob\u00e1 \u00e9 prorrogado ...}}\n\nA \"platform\" approach is proposed for construction to minimise environmental impact.\nThere would be no access roads, and workers would be taken to the site by helicopter.\nAfter construction is complete the site would be regenerated.{{sfn|Tapaj\u00f3s Basin Dams \u2013 International Rivers}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notes}}{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n{{stack|{{Portal|Brazil|Water|Renewable energy}}}}\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{citation|work=Hydro World|publisher=PennWell Corporation|ref={{harvid|Brazil sets concession auction for 8,040-MW Sao Luiz do Tapajos...}}\n |title=Brazil sets concession auction for 8,040-MW Sao Luiz do Tapajos hydro project|location=Brasilia|date=17 September 2014\n |url=http://www.hydroworld.com/articles/2014/09/brazil-sets-concession-auction-for-8-040-mw-sao-luiz-do-tapajos-hydro-project.html|accessdate=2017-02-13}}\n*{{citation |title=Usinas-plataforma: aposta no baixo impacto|date=7 May 2010\n |last=Couto |first=F\u00e1bio|language=pt|work=Canal Energia|publisher=Eletronorte\n |url=http://www.eletronorte.gov.br/opencms/opencms/modulos/noticia/noticia_0479.html?uri=/modulos/home_noticias.html|accessdate=2017-02-17}}\n*{{citation |language=pt|ref={{harvid|Jatob\u00e1 Perfil da usina \u2013Barragens na Amaz\u00f4nia}}\n |title=Jatob\u00e1 Perfil da usina|work=Barragens na Amaz\u00f4nia\n |url=http://dams-info.org/pt/dams/view/jatoba/|accessdate=2017-02-13}}\n*{{citation|language=pt|ref={{harvid|Jamanxim Perfil da usina}}\n |title=Jamanxim Perfil da usina|work=Barragens na Amaz\u00f4nia\n |url=http://dams-info.org/pt/dams/view/jamanxim/|accessdate=2017-02-15}}\n*{{citation|date=20 January 2016|language=pt|ref={{harvid|Prazo para entrega de estudos da UHE Jatob\u00e1 \u00e9 prorrogado ...}}|title=Prazo para entrega de estudos da UHE Jatob\u00e1 \u00e9 prorrogado at\u00e9 dezembro|work=Portal PCH|url=http://www.portalpch.com.br/5997-20-01-2016-prazo-para-entrega-de-estudos-da-uhe-jatoba-e-prorrogado-ate-dezembro.html|accessdate=2017-02-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170218063131/http://www.portalpch.com.br/5997-20-01-2016-prazo-para-entrega-de-estudos-da-uhe-jatoba-e-prorrogado-ate-dezembro.html|archive-date=18 February 2017|url-status=dead}}\n*{{citation|ref={{harvid|Tapaj\u00f3s Basin Dams \u2013 International Rivers}}\n |title=Tapaj\u00f3s Basin Dams|work=International Rivers\n |url=https://www.internationalrivers.org/resources/tapaj%C3%B3s-basin-dams-3352|accessdate=2017-02-13}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cachoeira dos Patos Dam}}\n[[Category:Hydroelectric power stations in Brazil]]\n[[Category:Dams in Par\u00e1]]\n[[Category:Proposed hydroelectric power stations|Jamanaxim Dam]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox dam\n| name                 = Jamanxim Dam\n| name_official        = Barragem Jardim Jamanxim\n| image                = \n| image_size           = 235\n| image_caption        = \n| image_alt            = \n| location_map         = Brazil\n| location_map_size    = \n| location_map_caption = \n| location_map_alt     = \n| coordinates          = {{coord|-5.658876|-55.874181|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n| country              = Brazil\n| location             = [[Itaituba]], Par\u00e1\n| purpose              = Hydroelectric\n| status               = Planned\n| construction_began   = \n| opening              = \n| demolished           = \n| cost                 = \n| owner                = \n| operator             = \n| dam_type             = \n| dam_crosses          = [[Jamanxim River]]\n| dam_height_foundation= \n| dam_height_thalweg   = {{convert|72|m}}\n| dam_length           = \n| dam_elevation_crest  = \n| dam_width_crest      = \n| dam_width_base       = \n| dam_volume           = \n| spillway_count       = \n| spillway_type        = \n| spillway_capacity    = \n| res_name             = \n| res_capacity_total   = \n| res_capacity_active  = \n| res_capacity_inactive= \n| res_catchment        = \n| res_surface          = {{convert|7400|ha}}\n| res_max_length       = \n| res_max_width        = \n| res_max_depth        = \n| res_elevation        = \n| res_tidal_range      = \n| plant_name           = \n| plant_coordinates    = \n| plant_operator       = \n| plant_commission     = \n| plant_decommission   = \n| plant_type           = \n| plant_hydraulic_head = \n| plant_turbines       = 3 [[Francis turbine]]s\n| plant_capacity       = {{convert|881|MW}}\n| plant_capacity_factor= \n| plant_annual_gen     = \n| website              = \n| extra                = \n}}\nThe '''Jamanxim Dam''' ({{lang-pt|Barragem Jamanxim}}) is a proposed hydroelectric dam on the [[Jamanxim River]] in the state of [[Par\u00e1]], Brazil.\n\n==Location==\n\nThe Jamanxim Dam is proposed to be built on the [[Jamanxim River]] in the state of Par\u00e1, in the [[Tapaj\u00f3s]] river basin.{{sfn|Jamanxim Perfil da usina}}\nIt would be built in the municipality of [[Itaituba]].\nThe dam would flood {{convert|8516|ha}} of the [[Jamanxim National Park]].\nIt would affect the [[South Amazon Ecotones Ecological Corridor]].{{sfn|Jamanxim Perfil da usina}}\n\nThe hydroelectric power plant will be part of the proposed {{convert|12,000|MW}} [[Tapaj\u00f3s hydroelectric complex]] on the Tapaj\u00f3s and Jamanxim rivers.{{sfn|Brazil sets concession auction for 8,040-MW Sao Luiz do Tapajos...}}\nOthers are the [[S\u00e3o Luiz do Tapaj\u00f3s Dam|S\u00e3o Luiz do Tapaj\u00f3s]] (6,133&nbsp;MW), [[Jatob\u00e1 Hydroelectric Power Plant|Jatob\u00e1]] (2,338&nbsp;MW), [[Cachoeira do Cai Dam|Cachoeira do Cai]] (802&nbsp;MW) and [[Cachoeira dos Patos Dam|Cachoeira dos Patos]] (528&nbsp;MW), all under study, as well as the [[Chacor\u00e3o Dam|Chacor\u00e3o]] (3,336&nbsp;MW) and [[Jardim do Ouro Dam|Jardim do Ouro]] (227&nbsp;MW).{{sfn|Jatob\u00e1 Perfil da usina \u2013Barragens na Amaz\u00f4nia}}\n\n==Technical==\n\nThe dam would be {{convert|72|m}} high, containing a reservoir with an area of {{convert|7445|ha}}.\nThe planned power plant would have potential of {{convert|881|MW}}, with guaranteed capacity of {{convert|475|MW}}.\nThe plant would contain 3 [[Francis turbine]]s, handling a flow of {{convert|1366|m3/s}}.{{sfn|Couto|2010}}\n\nEstimated cost would e US$984 million.\nThe project would be built by [[Eletrobras]], [[Eletronorte]], Constru\u00e7\u00f5es e Com\u00e9rcio Camargo C\u00f4rrea, EDF Consultoria em Projetos de Gera\u00e7\u00e3o de Energia, Endesa Brasil, EPP Energia El\u00e9trica, Promo\u00e7\u00e3o e Participa\u00e7\u00f5es, Neoenergia Investimentos and Odebrecht.{{sfn|Jamanxim Perfil da usina}}\n\n==Planning process==\n\nOn 20 January 2016 it was reported that the deadline for the feasibility study for the Jatob\u00e1 plant had been extended to December 2016, and the deadline for the Jamanxim plant feasibility study was now 31 December 2017.{{sfn|Prazo para entrega de estudos da UHE Jatob\u00e1 \u00e9 prorrogado ...}}\n\nA \"platform\" approach is proposed for construction to minimise environmental impact.\nThere would be no access roads, and workers would be taken to the site by helicopter.\nAfter construction is complete the site would be regenerated.{{sfn|Tapaj\u00f3s Basin Dams \u2013 International Rivers}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notes}}{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n{{stack|{{Portal|Brazil|Water|Renewable energy}}}}\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{citation|work=Hydro World|publisher=PennWell Corporation|ref={{harvid|Brazil sets concession auction for 8,040-MW Sao Luiz do Tapajos...}}\n |title=Brazil sets concession auction for 8,040-MW Sao Luiz do Tapajos hydro project|location=Brasilia|date=17 September 2014\n |url=http://www.hydroworld.com/articles/2014/09/brazil-sets-concession-auction-for-8-040-mw-sao-luiz-do-tapajos-hydro-project.html|accessdate=2017-02-13}}\n*{{citation |title=Usinas-plataforma: aposta no baixo impacto|date=7 May 2010\n |last=Couto |first=F\u00e1bio|language=pt|work=Canal Energia|publisher=Eletronorte\n |url=http://www.eletronorte.gov.br/opencms/opencms/modulos/noticia/noticia_0479.html?uri=/modulos/home_noticias.html|accessdate=2017-02-17}}\n*{{citation |language=pt|ref={{harvid|Jatob\u00e1 Perfil da usina \u2013Barragens na Amaz\u00f4nia}}\n |title=Jatob\u00e1 Perfil da usina|work=Barragens na Amaz\u00f4nia\n |url=http://dams-info.org/pt/dams/view/jatoba/|accessdate=2017-02-13}}\n*{{citation|language=pt|ref={{harvid|Jamanxim Perfil da usina}}\n |title=Jamanxim Perfil da usina|work=Barragens na Amaz\u00f4nia\n |url=http://dams-info.org/pt/dams/view/jamanxim/|accessdate=2017-02-15}}\n*{{citation|date=20 January 2016|language=pt|ref={{harvid|Prazo para entrega de estudos da UHE Jatob\u00e1 \u00e9 prorrogado ...}}|title=Prazo para entrega de estudos da UHE Jatob\u00e1 \u00e9 prorrogado at\u00e9 dezembro|work=Portal PCH|url=http://www.portalpch.com.br/5997-20-01-2016-prazo-para-entrega-de-estudos-da-uhe-jatoba-e-prorrogado-ate-dezembro.html|accessdate=2017-02-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170218063131/http://www.portalpch.com.br/5997-20-01-2016-prazo-para-entrega-de-estudos-da-uhe-jatoba-e-prorrogado-ate-dezembro.html|archive-date=18 February 2017|url-status=dead}}\n*{{citation|ref={{harvid|Tapaj\u00f3s Basin Dams \u2013 International Rivers}}\n |title=Tapaj\u00f3s Basin Dams|work=International Rivers\n |url=https://www.internationalrivers.org/resources/tapaj%C3%B3s-basin-dams-3352|accessdate=2017-02-13}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cachoeira dos Patos Dam}}\n[[Category:Hydroelectric power stations in Brazil]]\n[[Category:Dams in Par\u00e1]]\n[[Category:Proposed hydroelectric power stations]]\n", "name_user": "Macquaria", "label": "safe", "comment": "Change in category naming", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jamanxim_Dam"}
{"title_page": "Aldona Wos", "text_new": "{{short description|American ambassador}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Aldona Zofia Wos\n| office = Vice Chair of the [[President's Commission on White House Fellowships]]\n| image = File:Aldona Wos.jpg\n| president = [[Donald Trump]]\n| termstart = May 1, 2017\n| predecessor = Cheryl Dorsey\n| office2 = [[North Carolina Department of Health and Human Services|North Carolina Secretary of Health and Human Services]]\n| governor2 = [[Pat McCrory]]\n| termend2 = {{End date|2015|08|05}}\n| termstart2 = {{Start date|2013|01|05}}\n| successor2 = Rick Brajer\n| office3 = [[United States Ambassador to Estonia]]\n| president3 = [[George W. Bush]]\n| predecessor3 = Joseph M. DeThomas\n| successor3 = Stanley Davis Phillips\n| termend3 = {{End date|2006|12|17}}\n| termstart3 = {{Start date|2004|08|13}}\n| birth_date = {{birth year and age|1955}}\n| birth_place = [[Warsaw]], Poland\n| nationality = [[Polish American]]\n| party = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| residence = [[Greensboro, North Carolina]], U.S.\n}}\n'''Aldona Zofia Wos''' (born 1955) is a [[Polish Americans|Polish-American]] [[physician]] and politician who has served in various positions at several U.S. government agencies and nonprofit organizations. She was the [[United States Ambassador to Estonia|United States Ambassador]] to [[Estonia]] from 2004 until early December 2006. Wos was the fifth U.S. ambassador to Estonia since that country regained its independence in 1991. From 2013 until 2015, she was head of the [[North Carolina Department of Health and Human Services]]. As of May 2017, Wos serves as vice-chairwoman of the [[White House Fellows|President's Commission on White House Fellowships]], which is tasked with reviewing candidates for White House fellowships.\n\n==Biography==\n===Early life and medical career===\nWos is the daughter of Wanda and Paul Zenon Wos.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://archive.nytimes.com/query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage-9C07E5DB1E3AF937A35751C1A9659D8B63.html|title=Deaths Wos, Paul Zenon|date=2013-12-04|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-12-03|language=en-US}}</ref> Wos' father was part of the [[Home Army]] during the [[Occupation of Poland (1939\u20131945)|German and Soviet occupation of Poland]] in [[World War II]] and her Catholic family helped twelve Jews escape the [[Warsaw Ghetto]]. Wos' grandmother and aunts were imprisoned in [[Ravensbr\u00fcck concentration camp]], while her father and grandfather, Paul Wos, Sr., were held in [[Flossenb\u00fcrg concentration camp]]<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xYQvRapO7rcC|title=Code Name \u017begota: Rescuing Jews in Occupied Poland, 1942-1945 : the Most Dangerous Conspiracy in Wartime Europe|last=Tomaszewski|first=Irene|last2=Werbowski|first2=Tecia|date=2010|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=9780313383915|pages=151\u2013155|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.greensboro.com/news/political/bush-taps-city-woman-as-estonia-ambassador/article_7dea5f55-865b-5ced-aaa8-983fbd74ad4d.html|title=Bush taps city woman as Estonia ambassador|last=Williams|first=Matt|date=June 7, 2004|work=Greensboro News & Record|access-date=2017-12-01|language=en}}</ref> They survived to be reunited after the [[Allies of World War II|Allied Forces]] liberated the concentration camps. Aldona Wos was born in 1955<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://history.state.gov/departmenthistory/people/wos-aldona|title=Aldona Wos (1955- )|website=Office of the Historian, Bureau of Public Affairs|publisher=United States Department of State|language=en|access-date=2017-12-03}}</ref> in [[Warsaw]], where she lived until the age of six when her family moved to [[Long Island]], [[New York (state)|New York]].<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\nWos earned a medical degree from [[Medical University of Warsaw|Warsaw Medical Academy]],<ref name=\":2\" /> then returned to New York to complete her residency and fellowship with a specialty in [[Respiratory disease|lung diseases]].<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.postimees.ee/1605807/usa-suursaadik-wos-teatas-eestist-lahkumisest|title=USA suursaadik Wos teatas Eestist lahkumisest|last=M\u00e4ekivi|first=Mirjam|date=December 4, 2006|work=Postimees|access-date=2017-12-01|language=et}}</ref> Wos practiced medicine in Manhattan for eighteen years.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/boroughs/envoy-dad-saved-jews-article-1.562691|title=Envoy's Dad Saved Jews|last=Siemaszko|first=Corky|date=June 9, 2004|work=NY Daily News|access-date=2017-12-01|language=en}}</ref> As a physician, Wos worked in the fight against the spread of [[HIV]] and [[AIDS]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.newsobserver.com/2012/12/15/2547148/mccrory-picks-outside.html|title=McCrory picks outside the box for DHHS secretary|last=Christensen|first=Rob|date=December 15, 2012|work=News & Observer|access-date=December 1, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130101145233/http://www.newsobserver.com/2012/12/15/2547148/mccrory-picks-outside.html<!-- invalid archive entry -->|archivedate=January 1, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://virumaateataja.postimees.ee/2294779/suursaadik-kulastas-tapat|title=Suursaadik k\u00fclastas Tapat|last=Lo\u0161t\u0161ina|first=Marina|date=December 7, 2006|work=Virumaa Teataja|access-date=2017-12-01|language=et}}</ref>\n\n===Political career===\nIn 1997, Wos left her medical practice and moved to [[Greensboro, North Carolina|Greensboro]], [[North Carolina]] with her husband Louis DeJoy, who was CEO of New Breed Logistics Inc.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> from 1983 to 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/triad/news/2015/12/15/triad-ceo-retires-from-firm-that-bought-his.html|title=Triad CEO retires from firm that bought his company, joins board of directors|last=Arcieri|first=Katie|date=December 15, 2015|website=Triad Business Journal|access-date=2017-12-01}}</ref> In North Carolina, she and her husband have organized and hosted fundraisers for a number of national and state-level political campaigns, and have been significant contributors to several [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] candidates.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.greensboro.com/news/political/getting-ready-for-bush-visit/article_4f5c6874-accb-5373-a5ad-54d30c7b3f65.html|title=Getting ready for Bush visit|last=Binker|first=Mark|date=October 16, 2006|work=Greensboro News & Record|access-date=2017-12-01|language=en}}</ref> Wos raised nearly $1 million for the campaign to elect [[Elizabeth Dole]] to the [[United States Senate|U.S. Senate]] in the [[United States Senate election in North Carolina, 2002|2002 elections]]<ref name=\":5\" /> and served as vice chairwoman of [[George W. Bush]]'s North Carolina fund-raising organization.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.greensboro.com/news/post-is-chance-to-carry-on-tradition-area-woman-says/article_301e9afa-e00c-5387-9fd4-89db785b8a18.html|title=Post is chance to carry on tradition, area woman says|last=Perkins|first=Allison|date=August 19, 2004|work=Greensboro News & Record|access-date=2017-12-01|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2002, Wos was appointed to a seat on the board of directors of the [[United States Holocaust Memorial Museum|U.S. Holocaust Memorial Council]].<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.greensboro.com/activist-takes-on-causes-with-a-passion/article_5e56788a-1287-5b16-9a26-2e8a7dda649b.html|title=Activist Takes on Causes With Passion|last=Jeffries|first=Cynthia|date=October 12, 2002|work=Greensboro News & Record|access-date=2017-12-01|language=en}}</ref> President George W. Bush re-appointed her to second term on the council beginning in 2004.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.americanambassadors.org/index.cfm?fuseaction=Members.view&memberid=264|title=Membership: Aldona Z. Wos, M.D.|website=Council of American Ambassadors|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130414001118/http://www.americanambassadors.org/index.cfm?fuseaction=Members.view&memberid=264|archive-date=April 14, 2013|access-date=December 1, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2004, President Bush appointed Wos as the [[United States Ambassador to Estonia|U.S. Ambassador to Estonia]], for a three-year term.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":6\" /> She was sworn-in on August 13, 2004.<ref name=\":3\" /> As ambassador to Estonia, she helped organize the state visit of President Bush to Estonia, which took place on 27th and 28 November 2006.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.postimees.ee/1603375/usa-president-george-w-bush-saabus-eestisse|title=USA president George W. Bush saabus Eestisse|date=November 27, 2006|work=Postimees|access-date=2017-12-14|language=et}}</ref> For her efforts in facilitating US cooperation with the Estonian police, she was awarded a special police medal, given to her by [[Raivo Aeg]], the head of the [[Estonian Police]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://epl.delfi.ee/news/eesti/politseipeadirektor-tanas-usa-suursaadikut-aldona-wosi?id=51068248|title=Politseipeadirektor t\u00e4nas USA suursaadikut Aldona Wosi|last=Kaldoja|first=Kerttu|date=December 15, 2006|work=Eesti P\u00e4evaleht|access-date=2017-12-01}}</ref> She left her diplomatic post in December 2006.<ref name=\":3\" /> Wos was succeeded by Stanley Davis Phillips who was sworn in on April 16, 2007.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.postimees.ee/1651187/usa-uueks-suursaadikuks-eestis-saab-stanley-davis-phillips|title=USA uueks suursaadikuks Eestis saab Stanley Davis Phillips|last=Kamps|first=Mari|date=April 17, 2007|work=Postimees|access-date=2017-12-01|language=et}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2007, Polish President [[Lech Kaczy\u0144ski|Lech Kaczynski]] awarded Wos the [[Order of Merit of the Republic of Poland|Commander Cross of the Order of Merit of the Republic of Poland]].<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.greensboro.com/news/community/poland-honors-ex-envoy/article_230a72f9-6c2e-5893-8b7d-4c93f36c8f76.html|title=Poland honors ex-envoy|last=Seals|first=Ryan|date=April 5, 2007|work=Greensboro News & Record|access-date=2017-12-03|language=en}}</ref>\n\nWos was part of the second campaign to elect [[Pat McCrory]] as [[Governor of North Carolina]]. In May 2011, she hosted a luncheon for the Women for Pat McCrory in the lead-up to the former [[Mayor of Charlotte, North Carolina|Mayor of Charlotte]]'s announcement as a Republican candidate for the [[2012 North Carolina gubernatorial election]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.greensboro.com/news/political/mccrory-prepping-for-nd-run-in/article_c24c8aca-1949-54a4-9532-fc13fb9757a4.html|title=McCrory prepping for 2nd run in '12|last=Binker|first=Mark|date=May 20, 2011|work=Greensboro News & Record|access-date=2017-12-03|language=en}}</ref> She later served as co-chairwoman for the campaign<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.greensboro.com/news/political/ann-romney-to-visit-greensboro/article_f5d1d8d4-5d7c-5c12-b5e1-a016e93c09b2.html|title=Ann Romney to visit Greensboro|last=Fain|first=Travis|date=July 12, 2012|work=Greensboro News & Record|access-date=2017-12-03|language=en}}</ref> and after McCrory's win, she was a part of his transition team.<ref name=\":0\" /> In June 2012, Wos was appointed to the board of governors of the [[University of North Carolina]] by the state's Republican-controlled [[North Carolina General Assembly|General Assembly]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.greensboro.com/news/greensboro-doctor-named-to-unc-board/article_7835895a-6125-5d43-9d23-67935e114c66.html|title=Greensboro doctor named to UNC board|date=2012-06-28|work=Greensboro News & Record|access-date=2017-12-03|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==== Secretary of North Carolina Health and Human Services ====\n{{See also|North_Carolina_Department_of_Health_and_Human_Services#New_cabinet_hires_and_NC_Fast_.282013.29|label 1=North Carolina Department of Health and Human Services}}\n\nIn December 2012, North Carolina Governor-elect [[Pat McCrory]] announced that Wos will be a member of his [[North Carolina Cabinet|Cabinet]] as Secretary of the [[North Carolina Department of Health and Human Services|Department of Health and Human Services]] (DHHS).<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://projects.newsobserver.com/under_the_dome/mccrory_begins_naming_administration_members|title=McCrory begins naming administration members|last=Christensen|first=Rob|date=December 13, 2012|work=News & Observer|access-date=December 1, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131024150042/http://projects.newsobserver.com/under_the_dome/mccrory_begins_naming_administration_members|archive-date=October 24, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.greensboro.com/news/government/wos-named-dhhs-secretary-wos-to-lead-human-services/article_08e95af5-60a0-51f9-85c4-8b7dc0adfea8.html|title=Wos named DHHS secretary Wos to lead Human Services|last=Fain|first=Travis|date=December 13, 2012|work=Greensboro News & Record|access-date=2017-12-01|language=en}}</ref> Wos declined her $128,000 salary and was instead paid a token $1.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.journalnow.com/news/state_region/gov-pat-mccrory-gives-his-cabinet-generous-salary-hikes/article_1cf922f0-5bec-11e2-9571-0019bb30f31a.html|title=Gov. Pat McCrory gives his cabinet generous salary hikes|last=Frank|first=John|date=January 11, 2013|work=Winston-Salem Journal|access-date=2017-12-01|language=en}}</ref> On January 31, 2013, a performance audit was released, criticizing the previous administration's lack of record keeping concerning various funds, as well as naming other budgetary problems. Wos released her responses to the audit in an appendix, agreeing on all points with the auditor, including the conclusion that DHHS had consistently exceeded budgeted amounts for administrative costs due to lack of oversight by the previous administration.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ncauditor.net/epsweb/reports/performance/per-2013-7291.pdf|title=Performance Audit|last=Wood|first=Beth A.|date=January 31, 2013|website=State of North Carolina, Office of the State Auditor|access-date=December 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\nWhen speaking to the General Assembly in February 2013, Wos laid out her department priorities as \"[[Medicaid]] and information technology.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.northcarolinahealthnews.org/2013/02/14/dhhs-secretary-wos-lays-out-priorities-to-legislators/|title=DHHS Secretary Wos Lays Out Priorities to Legislators - North Carolina Health News|last=Hoban|first=Rose|date=2013-02-14|work=North Carolina Health News|access-date=2017-12-03|language=en-US}}</ref> In April 2013, Wos announced the governor's plan to overhaul the Medicaid system in North Carolina which she and McCrory criticized as \"broken\". This early plan would have brought in a few \"entities \u2014 likely including private companies \u2014 to function as insurance companies for Medicaid recipients.\" These entities would operate state-wide and serve as insurance plans from which Medicaid recipients can choose.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.greensboro.com/news/government/n-c-tackles-medicaid-reform/article_b70c6ed3-611e-50e9-a68d-285fd71ec80d.html|title=N.C. tackles Medicaid reform|last=Fain|first=Travis|date=April 14, 2013|work=Greensboro News & Record|access-date=2017-12-03|language=en}}</ref> The plan faced criticism from healthcare professionals who were concerned that it would permit \"out-of-state and for-profit providers to get a major foothold in North Carolina, rather than letting proven in-state and nonprofit providers, such as Community Care of N.C., take the lead\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.journalnow.com/news/local/wos-state-in-uncharted-waters-with-medicaid-reform/article_2e4a3d58-be9f-11e2-83cc-001a4bcf6878.html|title=Wos: State in uncharted waters with Medicaid reform|last=Craver|first=Richard|date=May 16, 2013|work=Winston-Salem Journal|access-date=2017-12-03|language=en}}</ref> It also suffered a possible setback when the person hired to spearhead this overhaul plan, Carol Steckel, resigned in September 2013 to join the private sector.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.greensboro.com/news/local_news/local-legislator-leads-team-looking-at-troubled-dhhs/article_1b0dcce2-295b-11e3-b011-0019bb30f31a.html|title=Local legislator leads team looking at troubled DHHS|last=Fain|first=Travis|date=September 29, 2013|work=Greensboro News & Record|access-date=2017-12-03|language=en}}</ref> The state chose not to implement the proposed plans.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.northcarolinahealthnews.org/2015/08/14/exclusive-dhhs-secretary-aldona-wos/|title=Exclusive: DHHS Secretary Aldona Wos - North Carolina Health News|last=Hoban|first=Rose|date=2015-08-14|work=North Carolina Health News|access-date=2017-12-03|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2013, DHHS went live with its NCTracks system for managing Medicaid billings,<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.wral.com/dhhs-faces-skeptical-questions-on-medicaid-payment-system/12972582/|title=DHHS faces skeptical questions on Medicaid payment system :: WRAL.com|last=Binker|first=Mark|date=October 8, 2013|work=WRAL.com|access-date=2017-12-03|language=en}}</ref> a system contracted in 2008 under the previous administration.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ncdhhs.gov/news/press-releases/dhhs-nctracks-earns-certification-federal-government|title=DHHS' NCTracks Earns Certification from Federal Government|date=April 12, 2015|website=NC Department of Health and Human Services|access-date=2017-12-03}}</ref> By October, the system was facing criticism from health care providers that were concerned that the system was not reimbursing them quickly enough.<ref name=\":9\" /> In January 2014, an error in the system caused the private medical information of almost 49,000 children to be mailed to the wrong addresses.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.greensboro.com/news/local_news/n-c-tells-usda-it-will-fix-food-stamp-problems/article_3c2ff8a6-7fc2-11e3-9a9f-0019bb30f31a.html|title=N.C. tells USDA it will fix food stamp problems before April|last=Associated Press|date=January 17, 2014|work=Greensboro News & Record|access-date=2017-12-14|language=en}}</ref> Throughout 2013 and early 2014, DHHS worked to resolve glitches with the NCTracks Medicaid billing system. The department announced that the system was working effectively by July 2014.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.wral.com/year-after-launch-nc-tracks-still-getting-mixed-reviews-from-medical-providers/13778900/|title=Year after launch, NCTracks still getting mixed reviews from medical providers :: WRAL.com|date=July 1, 2014|work=WRAL.com|access-date=2017-12-03|language=en}}</ref> Wos stated that she was disappointed that the state elected not to move forward with her proposal to reform the state's entire Medicaid program. By 2015, DHHS announced that the glitches in NCTracks were resolved, and Wos had \"[convinced] the legislature of the need to invest in the state's medical examiner system.\"<ref name=\":10\" />\n\nWos resigned on August 15, 2015, stating in a press conference that it was \"simply time to go home\" and spend time with her family. Asked by the press if she would \"change any of the decisions that she made over a sometimes rocky tenure,\" she replied, \"not at all.\" Wos was replaced by Rick Brajer, a former medical technology executive.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.wral.com/wos-resigns-as-dhhs-secretary-former-biotech-exec-taking-over/14812845/|title=Wos resigns as DHHS secretary, former biotech exec taking over :: WRAL.com|last=Binker|first=Mark|date=August 5, 2015|work=WRAL|access-date=2017-12-03|last2=Burns|first2=Matthew|language=en}}</ref> After being sworn in, Brajer asserted to the press that Wos' resignation was unrelated to the ongoing federal investigation into DHHS.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://wncn.com/2015/09/28/wos-did-not-resign-due-to-subpoenas-dhhs-head-says/|title=Wos did not resign due to subpoenas, DHHS head says|last=Rodriguez|first=Jonathan|date=2015-09-28|work=WNCN|access-date=2017-12-03|language=en-US}}</ref> In August 2016, federal officials ended the investigations into employee and consultant contracts \"with no finding of criminal wrongdoing\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.newsobserver.com/news/politics-government/state-politics/article95304957.html|title=Criminal investigation into state contracts closes|last=Blythe|first=Anne|date=August 12, 2016|work=The News & Observer|access-date=2017-12-03|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAlthough the Wos' tenure as secretary earned criticism for issues such as computer glitches, McCrory praised how she \"streamlined\" the health care delivery systems. McCrory also praised Wos for the state's $130 million Medicaid budget surplus during her tenure, after years of major budget shortfalls. For her service to the state, McCrory awarded Wos with the [[Order of the Long Leaf Pine]].<ref name=\":8\" />\n\n==== 2015 to present ====\nIn 2017 May, President [[Donald Trump]] appointed her his vice-chairwoman of the [[President's Commission on White House Fellowships]]. The president uses the commission to interview and recommend candidates for White House fellowships.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.newsobserver.com/news/politics-government/state-politics/article148048934.html|title=Aldona Wos, a former NC agency head, will help lead a White House commission for Trump|last=Bonner|first=Lynn|date=May 2, 2017|work=The News & Observer|access-date=2017-11-15|language=en}}</ref>  In June 2019, she was considered for [[List_of_ambassadors_of_the_United_States_to_Canada|Ambassador to Canada]].<ref>https://www.theglobeandmail.com/politics/article-trump-picks-former-bush-envoy-aldona-wos-as-next-ambassador-to-canada/</ref> Trump announced his intent to nominate her on February 11, 2020.<ref>https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/aldona-wos-new-us-ambassador-canada-1.5460207</ref> On February 25, 2020, her nomination was sent to the Senate.<ref>[https://www.whitehouse.gov/presidential-actions/eight-nominations-sent-senate-3/ \"Eight Nominations Sent to the Senate\", The White House, February 25, 2020]</ref> Her nomination is currently pending before the [[United States Senate Committee on Foreign Relations]].\n\n== Personal life ==\nWos and her husband DeJoy have twin children, Ania and Andrew.<ref name=\":2\" /> The family lives in Greensboro, North Carolina, in an Irving Park Neighborhood home<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.greensboro.com/news/general_assignment/newly-renovated-it-s-a-deal-at-million/article_643fd6fc-d72f-54ff-90bf-c74ba4a8a157.html|title=Newly renovated, it's a deal at $5.9 million|last=Schlosser|first=Jim|date=August 10, 2005|work=Greensboro News & Record|access-date=2017-12-03|last2=Moffett|first2=Margaret|language=en}}</ref> which has been the location of several notable political fund-raising events.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.greensboro.com/news/top-bush-aide-rove-comes-to-greensboro-for-gop-fund/article_1e9fedfb-d73c-5d84-8b3a-ba28417a175c.html|title=Top Bush aide Rove comes to Greensboro for GOP fund-raiser|date=September 15, 2005|work=Greensboro News & Record|access-date=2017-12-01|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.greensboro.com/news/political/bush-s-visit-to-greensboro-set/article_3663c6b2-dd8c-53b4-9314-671d3c799a46.html|title=Bush's visit to Greensboro set|last=Killian|first=Joe|date=October 13, 2006|work=Greensboro News & Record|access-date=2017-12-01|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.greensboro.com/news/government/it-could-ve-been-any-other-friday-in-irving-park/article_65a173e9-e494-5033-9656-b4a7fae659fd.html|title=It could've been any other Friday in Irving Park \u2014 except Trump was coming|last=Battaglia|first=Danielle|date=October 6, 2017|work=Greensboro News & Record|access-date=2017-12-01|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.greensboro.com/news/political/palin-to-guest-star-at-a-fundraiser-here/article_f27170a0-533c-546c-9987-6779246a3e32.html|title=Palin to guest star at a fundraiser here|last=Binker|first=Mark|date=October 1, 2008|work=Greensboro News & Record|access-date=2017-12-01|language=en}}</ref>\n\nWos has been involved in efforts to raise money for a number of non-profit organizations and private schools as well. She served on the board of the [[United Way of America|United Way]] of Greater Greensboro,<ref name=\":6\" /> and has been involved with the Family Services of the Piedmont, Hospice and Palliative Care of Greensboro, and the [[Triad Stage|Triad Stage Theatre]].<ref name=\":7\" /> She was also instrumental in raising the finances for the [[Greensboro Ballet]] gala, held in February 2011, to celebrate the 30th anniversary of the [[ballet company]] and school once attended by her children.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.greensboro.com/life/all-they-want-to-do-is-dance/article_79fdf8c2-121d-5eab-bdf5-ef23c19fe353.html|title=All they want to do is dance|last=DeCwikiel-Kane|first=Dawn|date=February 4, 2011|work=Greensboro News & Record|access-date=2017-12-03|language=en}}</ref> Wos and DeJoy also founded The Louis DeJoy and Aldona Z. Wos Family Foundation which awards several scholarships to students.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.greensboro.com/blogs/gotriad_extra/emf-students-receive-scholarships-from-louis-dejoy-and-aldona-wos/article_6fcd1177-31c3-5410-b510-5c7d4a4391f7.html|title=8 EMF students receive scholarships from Louis DeJoy and Aldona Wos Family Foundation|date=May 22, 2017|work=Greensboro News & Record|access-date=2017-11-15|language=en}}</ref> The foundation also hosts a [[Pro\u2013am|professional\u2013amateur]] golf championship as a prelude to the [[Wyndham Championship]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.journalnow.com/sports/golf/wyndham/country-singer-n-c-native-eric-church-hits-the-right/article_ac0f6aa5-9215-5815-94c1-56598e299d2c.html|title=Country singer, N.C. native Eric Church hits the right notes at Sedgefield Country Club|last=Spencer|first=Turkin|date=August 17, 2016|work=Winston-Salem Journal|access-date=2017-11-15|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.greensboro.com/sports/golf/wyndham/schlosser-s-shots-amateurs-help-pros-get-wyndham-week-under/article_48f72e9e-8133-11e7-a26c-a3ac60db8e12.html|title=Schlosser's Shots: Amateurs help pros get Wyndham Week under way|last=Schlosser|first=Jim|date=August 14, 2017|work=Greensboro News & Record|access-date=2017-11-15|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://louisdejoyandaldonawosfamilyfoundation.com/ Official website of The Louis DeJoy and Aldona Z. Wos Family Foundation]\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-dip}}\n{{succession box|before=Joseph M. DeThomas|title=[[United States Ambassador to Estonia]]|years=2004\u20132006|after=Stanley Davis Phillips}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wos, Aldona}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Date of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:State cabinet secretaries of North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of the United States to Estonia]]\n[[Category:Polish emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:People from Warsaw]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Cross of Terra Mariana, 1st Class]]\n[[Category:North Carolina Republicans]]\n[[Category:American women diplomats]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Merit of the Republic of Poland]]\n[[Category:Medical University of Warsaw alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American ambassador}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Aldona Zofia Wos\n| office = Vice Chair of the [[President's Commission on White House Fellowships]]\n| image = File:Aldona Wos.jpg\n| president = [[Donald Trump]]\n| termstart = May 1, 2017\n| predecessor = Cheryl Dorsey\n| office2 = [[North Carolina Department of Health and Human Services|North Carolina Secretary of Health and Human Services]]\n| governor2 = [[Pat McCrory]]\n| termend2 = {{End date|2015|08|05}}\n| termstart2 = {{Start date|2013|01|05}}\n| successor2 = Rick Brajer\n| office3 = [[United States Ambassador to Estonia]]\n| president3 = [[George W. Bush]]\n| predecessor3 = Joseph M. DeThomas\n| successor3 = Stanley Davis Phillips\n| termend3 = {{End date|2006|12|17}}\n| termstart3 = {{Start date|2004|08|13}}\n| birth_date = {{birth year and age|1955}}\n| birth_place = [[Warsaw]], Poland\n| nationality = [[Polish American]]\n| party = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| residence = [[Greensboro, North Carolina]], U.S.\n}}\n'''Aldona Zofia Wos''' (born 1955) is a [[Polish Americans|Polish-American]] [[physician]] and politician who has served in various positions at several U.S. government agencies and nonprofit organizations. She was the [[United States Ambassador to Estonia|United States Ambassador]] to [[Estonia]] from 2004 until early December 2006. Wos was the fifth U.S. ambassador to Estonia since that country regained its independence in 1991. From 2013 until 2015, she was head of the [[North Carolina Department of Health and Human Services]]. As of May 2017, Wos serves as vice-chairwoman of the [[White House Fellows|President's Commission on White House Fellowships]], which is tasked with reviewing candidates for White House fellowships.\n\n==Biography==\n===Early life and medical career===\nWos is the daughter of Wanda and Paul Zenon Wos.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://archive.nytimes.com/query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage-9C07E5DB1E3AF937A35751C1A9659D8B63.html|title=Deaths Wos, Paul Zenon|date=2013-12-04|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-12-03|language=en-US}}</ref> Wos' father was part of the [[Home Army]] during the [[Occupation of Poland (1939\u20131945)|German and Soviet occupation of Poland]] in [[World War II]] and her Catholic family helped twelve Jews escape the [[Warsaw Ghetto]]. Wos' grandmother and aunts were imprisoned in [[Ravensbr\u00fcck concentration camp]], while her father and grandfather, Paul Wos, Sr., were held in [[Flossenb\u00fcrg concentration camp]]<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xYQvRapO7rcC|title=Code Name \u017begota: Rescuing Jews in Occupied Poland, 1942-1945 : the Most Dangerous Conspiracy in Wartime Europe|last=Tomaszewski|first=Irene|last2=Werbowski|first2=Tecia|date=2010|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=9780313383915|pages=151\u2013155|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.greensboro.com/news/political/bush-taps-city-woman-as-estonia-ambassador/article_7dea5f55-865b-5ced-aaa8-983fbd74ad4d.html|title=Bush taps city woman as Estonia ambassador|last=Williams|first=Matt|date=June 7, 2004|work=Greensboro News & Record|access-date=2017-12-01|language=en}}</ref> They survived to be reunited after the [[Allies of World War II|Allied Forces]] liberated the concentration camps. Aldona Wos was born in 1955<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://history.state.gov/departmenthistory/people/wos-aldona|title=Aldona Wos (1955- )|website=Office of the Historian, Bureau of Public Affairs|publisher=United States Department of State|language=en|access-date=2017-12-03}}</ref> in [[Warsaw]], where she lived until the age of six when her family moved to [[Long Island]], [[New York (state)|New York]].<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\nWos earned a medical degree from Warsaw Medical Academy,<ref name=\":2\" /> then returned to New York to complete her residency and fellowship with a specialty in [[Respiratory disease|lung diseases]].<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.postimees.ee/1605807/usa-suursaadik-wos-teatas-eestist-lahkumisest|title=USA suursaadik Wos teatas Eestist lahkumisest|last=M\u00e4ekivi|first=Mirjam|date=December 4, 2006|work=Postimees|access-date=2017-12-01|language=et}}</ref> Wos practiced medicine in Manhattan for eighteen years.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/boroughs/envoy-dad-saved-jews-article-1.562691|title=Envoy's Dad Saved Jews|last=Siemaszko|first=Corky|date=June 9, 2004|work=NY Daily News|access-date=2017-12-01|language=en}}</ref> As a physician, Wos worked in the fight against the spread of [[HIV]] and [[AIDS]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.newsobserver.com/2012/12/15/2547148/mccrory-picks-outside.html|title=McCrory picks outside the box for DHHS secretary|last=Christensen|first=Rob|date=December 15, 2012|work=News & Observer|access-date=December 1, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130101145233/http://www.newsobserver.com/2012/12/15/2547148/mccrory-picks-outside.html<!-- invalid archive entry -->|archivedate=January 1, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://virumaateataja.postimees.ee/2294779/suursaadik-kulastas-tapat|title=Suursaadik k\u00fclastas Tapat|last=Lo\u0161t\u0161ina|first=Marina|date=December 7, 2006|work=Virumaa Teataja|access-date=2017-12-01|language=et}}</ref>\n\n===Political career===\nIn 1997, Wos left her medical practice and moved to [[Greensboro, North Carolina|Greensboro]], [[North Carolina]] with her husband Louis DeJoy, who was CEO of New Breed Logistics Inc.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> from 1983 to 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/triad/news/2015/12/15/triad-ceo-retires-from-firm-that-bought-his.html|title=Triad CEO retires from firm that bought his company, joins board of directors|last=Arcieri|first=Katie|date=December 15, 2015|website=Triad Business Journal|access-date=2017-12-01}}</ref> In North Carolina, she and her husband have organized and hosted fundraisers for a number of national and state-level political campaigns, and have been significant contributors to several [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] candidates.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.greensboro.com/news/political/getting-ready-for-bush-visit/article_4f5c6874-accb-5373-a5ad-54d30c7b3f65.html|title=Getting ready for Bush visit|last=Binker|first=Mark|date=October 16, 2006|work=Greensboro News & Record|access-date=2017-12-01|language=en}}</ref> Wos raised nearly $1 million for the campaign to elect [[Elizabeth Dole]] to the [[United States Senate|U.S. Senate]] in the [[United States Senate election in North Carolina, 2002|2002 elections]]<ref name=\":5\" /> and served as vice chairwoman of [[George W. Bush]]'s North Carolina fund-raising organization.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.greensboro.com/news/post-is-chance-to-carry-on-tradition-area-woman-says/article_301e9afa-e00c-5387-9fd4-89db785b8a18.html|title=Post is chance to carry on tradition, area woman says|last=Perkins|first=Allison|date=August 19, 2004|work=Greensboro News & Record|access-date=2017-12-01|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2002, Wos was appointed to a seat on the board of directors of the [[United States Holocaust Memorial Museum|U.S. Holocaust Memorial Council]].<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.greensboro.com/activist-takes-on-causes-with-a-passion/article_5e56788a-1287-5b16-9a26-2e8a7dda649b.html|title=Activist Takes on Causes With Passion|last=Jeffries|first=Cynthia|date=October 12, 2002|work=Greensboro News & Record|access-date=2017-12-01|language=en}}</ref> President George W. Bush re-appointed her to second term on the council beginning in 2004.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.americanambassadors.org/index.cfm?fuseaction=Members.view&memberid=264|title=Membership: Aldona Z. Wos, M.D.|website=Council of American Ambassadors|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130414001118/http://www.americanambassadors.org/index.cfm?fuseaction=Members.view&memberid=264|archive-date=April 14, 2013|access-date=December 1, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2004, President Bush appointed Wos as the [[United States Ambassador to Estonia|U.S. Ambassador to Estonia]], for a three-year term.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":6\" /> She was sworn-in on August 13, 2004.<ref name=\":3\" /> As ambassador to Estonia, she helped organize the state visit of President Bush to Estonia, which took place on 27th and 28 November 2006.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.postimees.ee/1603375/usa-president-george-w-bush-saabus-eestisse|title=USA president George W. Bush saabus Eestisse|date=November 27, 2006|work=Postimees|access-date=2017-12-14|language=et}}</ref> For her efforts in facilitating US cooperation with the Estonian police, she was awarded a special police medal, given to her by Raivo Aeg, the head of the [[Estonian Police]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://epl.delfi.ee/news/eesti/politseipeadirektor-tanas-usa-suursaadikut-aldona-wosi?id=51068248|title=Politseipeadirektor t\u00e4nas USA suursaadikut Aldona Wosi|last=Kaldoja|first=Kerttu|date=December 15, 2006|work=Eesti P\u00e4evaleht|access-date=2017-12-01}}</ref> She left her diplomatic post in December 2006.<ref name=\":3\" /> Wos was succeeded by Stanley Davis Phillips who was sworn in on April 16, 2007.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.postimees.ee/1651187/usa-uueks-suursaadikuks-eestis-saab-stanley-davis-phillips|title=USA uueks suursaadikuks Eestis saab Stanley Davis Phillips|last=Kamps|first=Mari|date=April 17, 2007|work=Postimees|access-date=2017-12-01|language=et}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2007, Polish President [[Lech Kaczy\u0144ski|Lech Kaczynski]] awarded Wos the [[Order of Merit of the Republic of Poland|Commander Cross of the Order of Merit of the Republic of Poland]].<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.greensboro.com/news/community/poland-honors-ex-envoy/article_230a72f9-6c2e-5893-8b7d-4c93f36c8f76.html|title=Poland honors ex-envoy|last=Seals|first=Ryan|date=April 5, 2007|work=Greensboro News & Record|access-date=2017-12-03|language=en}}</ref>\n\nWos was part of the second campaign to elect [[Pat McCrory]] as [[Governor of North Carolina]]. In May 2011, she hosted a luncheon for the Women for Pat McCrory in the lead-up to the former [[Mayor of Charlotte, North Carolina|Mayor of Charlotte]]'s announcement as a Republican candidate for the [[2012 North Carolina gubernatorial election]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.greensboro.com/news/political/mccrory-prepping-for-nd-run-in/article_c24c8aca-1949-54a4-9532-fc13fb9757a4.html|title=McCrory prepping for 2nd run in '12|last=Binker|first=Mark|date=May 20, 2011|work=Greensboro News & Record|access-date=2017-12-03|language=en}}</ref> She later served as co-chairwoman for the campaign<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.greensboro.com/news/political/ann-romney-to-visit-greensboro/article_f5d1d8d4-5d7c-5c12-b5e1-a016e93c09b2.html|title=Ann Romney to visit Greensboro|last=Fain|first=Travis|date=July 12, 2012|work=Greensboro News & Record|access-date=2017-12-03|language=en}}</ref> and after McCrory's win, she was a part of his transition team.<ref name=\":0\" /> In June 2012, Wos was appointed to the board of governors of the [[University of North Carolina]] by the state's Republican-controlled [[North Carolina General Assembly|General Assembly]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.greensboro.com/news/greensboro-doctor-named-to-unc-board/article_7835895a-6125-5d43-9d23-67935e114c66.html|title=Greensboro doctor named to UNC board|date=2012-06-28|work=Greensboro News & Record|access-date=2017-12-03|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==== Secretary of North Carolina Health and Human Services ====\n{{See also|North_Carolina_Department_of_Health_and_Human_Services#New_cabinet_hires_and_NC_Fast_.282013.29|label 1=North Carolina Department of Health and Human Services}}\n\nIn December 2012, North Carolina Governor-elect [[Pat McCrory]] announced that Wos will be a member of his [[North Carolina Cabinet|Cabinet]] as Secretary of the [[North Carolina Department of Health and Human Services|Department of Health and Human Services]] (DHHS).<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://projects.newsobserver.com/under_the_dome/mccrory_begins_naming_administration_members|title=McCrory begins naming administration members|last=Christensen|first=Rob|date=December 13, 2012|work=News & Observer|access-date=December 1, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131024150042/http://projects.newsobserver.com/under_the_dome/mccrory_begins_naming_administration_members|archive-date=October 24, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.greensboro.com/news/government/wos-named-dhhs-secretary-wos-to-lead-human-services/article_08e95af5-60a0-51f9-85c4-8b7dc0adfea8.html|title=Wos named DHHS secretary Wos to lead Human Services|last=Fain|first=Travis|date=December 13, 2012|work=Greensboro News & Record|access-date=2017-12-01|language=en}}</ref> Wos declined her $128,000 salary and was instead paid a token $1.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.journalnow.com/news/state_region/gov-pat-mccrory-gives-his-cabinet-generous-salary-hikes/article_1cf922f0-5bec-11e2-9571-0019bb30f31a.html|title=Gov. Pat McCrory gives his cabinet generous salary hikes|last=Frank|first=John|date=January 11, 2013|work=Winston-Salem Journal|access-date=2017-12-01|language=en}}</ref> On January 31, 2013, a performance audit was released, criticizing the previous administration's lack of record keeping concerning various funds, as well as naming other budgetary problems. Wos released her responses to the audit in an appendix, agreeing on all points with the auditor, including the conclusion that DHHS had consistently exceeded budgeted amounts for administrative costs due to lack of oversight by the previous administration.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ncauditor.net/epsweb/reports/performance/per-2013-7291.pdf|title=Performance Audit|last=Wood|first=Beth A.|date=January 31, 2013|website=State of North Carolina, Office of the State Auditor|access-date=December 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\nWhen speaking to the General Assembly in February 2013, Wos laid out her department priorities as \"[[Medicaid]] and information technology.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.northcarolinahealthnews.org/2013/02/14/dhhs-secretary-wos-lays-out-priorities-to-legislators/|title=DHHS Secretary Wos Lays Out Priorities to Legislators - North Carolina Health News|last=Hoban|first=Rose|date=2013-02-14|work=North Carolina Health News|access-date=2017-12-03|language=en-US}}</ref> In April 2013, Wos announced the governor's plan to overhaul the Medicaid system in North Carolina which she and McCrory criticized as \"broken\". This early plan would have brought in a few \"entities \u2014 likely including private companies \u2014 to function as insurance companies for Medicaid recipients.\" These entities would operate state-wide and serve as insurance plans from which Medicaid recipients can choose.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.greensboro.com/news/government/n-c-tackles-medicaid-reform/article_b70c6ed3-611e-50e9-a68d-285fd71ec80d.html|title=N.C. tackles Medicaid reform|last=Fain|first=Travis|date=April 14, 2013|work=Greensboro News & Record|access-date=2017-12-03|language=en}}</ref> The plan faced criticism from healthcare professionals who were concerned that it would permit \"out-of-state and for-profit providers to get a major foothold in North Carolina, rather than letting proven in-state and nonprofit providers, such as Community Care of N.C., take the lead\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.journalnow.com/news/local/wos-state-in-uncharted-waters-with-medicaid-reform/article_2e4a3d58-be9f-11e2-83cc-001a4bcf6878.html|title=Wos: State in uncharted waters with Medicaid reform|last=Craver|first=Richard|date=May 16, 2013|work=Winston-Salem Journal|access-date=2017-12-03|language=en}}</ref> It also suffered a possible setback when the person hired to spearhead this overhaul plan, Carol Steckel, resigned in September 2013 to join the private sector.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.greensboro.com/news/local_news/local-legislator-leads-team-looking-at-troubled-dhhs/article_1b0dcce2-295b-11e3-b011-0019bb30f31a.html|title=Local legislator leads team looking at troubled DHHS|last=Fain|first=Travis|date=September 29, 2013|work=Greensboro News & Record|access-date=2017-12-03|language=en}}</ref> The state chose not to implement the proposed plans.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.northcarolinahealthnews.org/2015/08/14/exclusive-dhhs-secretary-aldona-wos/|title=Exclusive: DHHS Secretary Aldona Wos - North Carolina Health News|last=Hoban|first=Rose|date=2015-08-14|work=North Carolina Health News|access-date=2017-12-03|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2013, DHHS went live with its NCTracks system for managing Medicaid billings,<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.wral.com/dhhs-faces-skeptical-questions-on-medicaid-payment-system/12972582/|title=DHHS faces skeptical questions on Medicaid payment system :: WRAL.com|last=Binker|first=Mark|date=October 8, 2013|work=WRAL.com|access-date=2017-12-03|language=en}}</ref> a system contracted in 2008 under the previous administration.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ncdhhs.gov/news/press-releases/dhhs-nctracks-earns-certification-federal-government|title=DHHS' NCTracks Earns Certification from Federal Government|date=April 12, 2015|website=NC Department of Health and Human Services|access-date=2017-12-03}}</ref> By October, the system was facing criticism from health care providers that were concerned that the system was not reimbursing them quickly enough.<ref name=\":9\" /> In January 2014, an error in the system caused the private medical information of almost 49,000 children to be mailed to the wrong addresses.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.greensboro.com/news/local_news/n-c-tells-usda-it-will-fix-food-stamp-problems/article_3c2ff8a6-7fc2-11e3-9a9f-0019bb30f31a.html|title=N.C. tells USDA it will fix food stamp problems before April|last=Associated Press|date=January 17, 2014|work=Greensboro News & Record|access-date=2017-12-14|language=en}}</ref> Throughout 2013 and early 2014, DHHS worked to resolve glitches with the NCTracks Medicaid billing system. The department announced that the system was working effectively by July 2014.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.wral.com/year-after-launch-nc-tracks-still-getting-mixed-reviews-from-medical-providers/13778900/|title=Year after launch, NCTracks still getting mixed reviews from medical providers :: WRAL.com|date=July 1, 2014|work=WRAL.com|access-date=2017-12-03|language=en}}</ref> Wos stated that she was disappointed that the state elected not to move forward with her proposal to reform the state's entire Medicaid program. By 2015, DHHS announced that the glitches in NCTracks were resolved, and Wos had \"[convinced] the legislature of the need to invest in the state's medical examiner system.\"<ref name=\":10\" />\n\nWos resigned on August 15, 2015, stating in a press conference that it was \"simply time to go home\" and spend time with her family. Asked by the press if she would \"change any of the decisions that she made over a sometimes rocky tenure,\" she replied, \"not at all.\" Wos was replaced by Rick Brajer, a former medical technology executive.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.wral.com/wos-resigns-as-dhhs-secretary-former-biotech-exec-taking-over/14812845/|title=Wos resigns as DHHS secretary, former biotech exec taking over :: WRAL.com|last=Binker|first=Mark|date=August 5, 2015|work=WRAL|access-date=2017-12-03|last2=Burns|first2=Matthew|language=en}}</ref> After being sworn in, Brajer asserted to the press that Wos' resignation was unrelated to the ongoing federal investigation into DHHS.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://wncn.com/2015/09/28/wos-did-not-resign-due-to-subpoenas-dhhs-head-says/|title=Wos did not resign due to subpoenas, DHHS head says|last=Rodriguez|first=Jonathan|date=2015-09-28|work=WNCN|access-date=2017-12-03|language=en-US}}</ref> In August 2016, federal officials ended the investigations into employee and consultant contracts \"with no finding of criminal wrongdoing\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.newsobserver.com/news/politics-government/state-politics/article95304957.html|title=Criminal investigation into state contracts closes|last=Blythe|first=Anne|date=August 12, 2016|work=The News & Observer|access-date=2017-12-03|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAlthough the Wos' tenure as secretary earned criticism for issues such as computer glitches, McCrory praised how she \"streamlined\" the health care delivery systems. McCrory also praised Wos for the state's $130 million Medicaid budget surplus during her tenure, after years of major budget shortfalls. For her service to the state, McCrory awarded Wos with the [[Order of the Long Leaf Pine]].<ref name=\":8\" />\n\n==== 2015 to present ====\nIn 2017 May, President [[Donald Trump]] appointed her his vice-chairwoman of the [[President's Commission on White House Fellowships]]. The president uses the commission to interview and recommend candidates for White House fellowships.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.newsobserver.com/news/politics-government/state-politics/article148048934.html|title=Aldona Wos, a former NC agency head, will help lead a White House commission for Trump|last=Bonner|first=Lynn|date=May 2, 2017|work=The News & Observer|access-date=2017-11-15|language=en}}</ref>  In June 2019, she was considered for [[List_of_ambassadors_of_the_United_States_to_Canada|Ambassador to Canada]].<ref>https://www.theglobeandmail.com/politics/article-trump-picks-former-bush-envoy-aldona-wos-as-next-ambassador-to-canada/</ref> Trump announced his intent to nominate her on February 11, 2020.<ref>https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/aldona-wos-new-us-ambassador-canada-1.5460207</ref> On February 25, 2020, her nomination was sent to the Senate.<ref>[https://www.whitehouse.gov/presidential-actions/eight-nominations-sent-senate-3/ \"Eight Nominations Sent to the Senate\", The White House, February 25, 2020]</ref> Her nomination is currently pending before the [[United States Senate Committee on Foreign Relations]].\n\n== Personal life ==\nWos and her husband DeJoy have twin children, Ania and Andrew.<ref name=\":2\" /> The family lives in Greensboro, North Carolina, in an Irving Park Neighborhood home<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.greensboro.com/news/general_assignment/newly-renovated-it-s-a-deal-at-million/article_643fd6fc-d72f-54ff-90bf-c74ba4a8a157.html|title=Newly renovated, it's a deal at $5.9 million|last=Schlosser|first=Jim|date=August 10, 2005|work=Greensboro News & Record|access-date=2017-12-03|last2=Moffett|first2=Margaret|language=en}}</ref> which has been the location of several notable political fund-raising events.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.greensboro.com/news/top-bush-aide-rove-comes-to-greensboro-for-gop-fund/article_1e9fedfb-d73c-5d84-8b3a-ba28417a175c.html|title=Top Bush aide Rove comes to Greensboro for GOP fund-raiser|date=September 15, 2005|work=Greensboro News & Record|access-date=2017-12-01|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.greensboro.com/news/political/bush-s-visit-to-greensboro-set/article_3663c6b2-dd8c-53b4-9314-671d3c799a46.html|title=Bush's visit to Greensboro set|last=Killian|first=Joe|date=October 13, 2006|work=Greensboro News & Record|access-date=2017-12-01|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.greensboro.com/news/government/it-could-ve-been-any-other-friday-in-irving-park/article_65a173e9-e494-5033-9656-b4a7fae659fd.html|title=It could've been any other Friday in Irving Park \u2014 except Trump was coming|last=Battaglia|first=Danielle|date=October 6, 2017|work=Greensboro News & Record|access-date=2017-12-01|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.greensboro.com/news/political/palin-to-guest-star-at-a-fundraiser-here/article_f27170a0-533c-546c-9987-6779246a3e32.html|title=Palin to guest star at a fundraiser here|last=Binker|first=Mark|date=October 1, 2008|work=Greensboro News & Record|access-date=2017-12-01|language=en}}</ref>\n\nWos has been involved in efforts to raise money for a number of non-profit organizations and private schools as well. She served on the board of the [[United Way of America|United Way]] of Greater Greensboro,<ref name=\":6\" /> and has been involved with the Family Services of the Piedmont, Hospice and Palliative Care of Greensboro, and the [[Triad Stage|Triad Stage Theatre]].<ref name=\":7\" /> She was also instrumental in raising the finances for the [[Greensboro Ballet]] gala, held in February 2011, to celebrate the 30th anniversary of the [[ballet company]] and school once attended by her children.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.greensboro.com/life/all-they-want-to-do-is-dance/article_79fdf8c2-121d-5eab-bdf5-ef23c19fe353.html|title=All they want to do is dance|last=DeCwikiel-Kane|first=Dawn|date=February 4, 2011|work=Greensboro News & Record|access-date=2017-12-03|language=en}}</ref> Wos and DeJoy also founded The Louis DeJoy and Aldona Z. Wos Family Foundation which awards several scholarships to students.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.greensboro.com/blogs/gotriad_extra/emf-students-receive-scholarships-from-louis-dejoy-and-aldona-wos/article_6fcd1177-31c3-5410-b510-5c7d4a4391f7.html|title=8 EMF students receive scholarships from Louis DeJoy and Aldona Wos Family Foundation|date=May 22, 2017|work=Greensboro News & Record|access-date=2017-11-15|language=en}}</ref> The foundation also hosts a [[Pro\u2013am|professional\u2013amateur]] golf championship as a prelude to the [[Wyndham Championship]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.journalnow.com/sports/golf/wyndham/country-singer-n-c-native-eric-church-hits-the-right/article_ac0f6aa5-9215-5815-94c1-56598e299d2c.html|title=Country singer, N.C. native Eric Church hits the right notes at Sedgefield Country Club|last=Spencer|first=Turkin|date=August 17, 2016|work=Winston-Salem Journal|access-date=2017-11-15|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.greensboro.com/sports/golf/wyndham/schlosser-s-shots-amateurs-help-pros-get-wyndham-week-under/article_48f72e9e-8133-11e7-a26c-a3ac60db8e12.html|title=Schlosser's Shots: Amateurs help pros get Wyndham Week under way|last=Schlosser|first=Jim|date=August 14, 2017|work=Greensboro News & Record|access-date=2017-11-15|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://louisdejoyandaldonawosfamilyfoundation.com/ Official website of The Louis DeJoy and Aldona Z. Wos Family Foundation]\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-dip}}\n{{succession box|before=Joseph M. DeThomas|title=[[United States Ambassador to Estonia]]|years=2004\u20132006|after=Stanley Davis Phillips}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wos, Aldona}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Date of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:State cabinet secretaries of North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of the United States to Estonia]]\n[[Category:Polish emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:People from Warsaw]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Cross of Terra Mariana, 1st Class]]\n[[Category:North Carolina Republicans]]\n[[Category:American women diplomats]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Merit of the Republic of Poland]]\n[[Category:Medical University of Warsaw alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Teukros", "label": "safe", "comment": "authority control and some wikilinks", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aldona_Wos"}
{"title_page": "Lee Zeldin", "text_new": "{{COI|date=September 2018}}\n{{short description|U.S. Representative from New York}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name          = Lee Zeldin\n|image         = Lee Zeldin new official portrait.jpg\n|state         = [[New York (state)|New York]]\n|district      = {{ushr|NY|1|1st}}\n|term_start    = January 3, 2015\n|term_end      = \n|predecessor   = [[Tim Bishop]]\n|successor     = \n|state_senate1 = New York State\n|district1     = [[New York's 3rd State Senate district|3rd]]\n|term_start1   = January 1, 2011\n|term_end1     = December 31, 2014\n|predecessor1  = [[Brian X. Foley]]\n|successor1    = [[Thomas Croci]]\n|birth_name    = Lee Michael Zeldin\n|birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1980|1|30}}\n|birth_place   = [[East Meadow, New York]], U.S.\n|death_date    = \n|death_place   = \n|party         = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse        = Diana Zeldin\n|children      = 2\n|education     = [[University at Albany, SUNY|State University of New York, Albany]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[Albany Law School]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n|signature     = Lee Zeldin's Signature.png\n|website       = {{url|zeldin.house.gov|House website}}\n|allegiance    = {{flag|United States}}\n|branch        = {{army|United States}}\n|serviceyears  = 2003\u2013present\n|rank          = [[File:US-O5 insignia.svg|15px]] [[Lieutenant colonel (United States)|Lieutenant Colonel]]\n|battles       = [[Iraq War]]\n}}\n'''Lee Michael Zeldin''' (born January 30, 1980) is an American attorney and politician serving as the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|NY|1}} since 2015. The district includes central and eastern [[Suffolk County, New York]], including most of [[Smithtown, New York|Smithtown]], as well as the towns of [[Brookhaven, New York|Brookhaven]], [[Riverhead (town), New York|Riverhead]], [[Southold, New York|Southold]], [[Southampton (town), New York|Southampton]], [[East Hampton (town), New York|East Hampton]] and [[Shelter Island (town), New York|Shelter Island, New York]]. A member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]], Zeldin previously served as the [[New York State Senate|New York State Senator]] from the [[New York's 3rd State Senate district|3rd district]] from 2011 to 2014.\n\n==Early life and education==\nZeldin was born in [[East Meadow, New York]], the son of Merrill Schwartz and David Zeldin.<ref>{{cite web|last=Civiletti|first=Denise|url=https://riverheadlocal.com/2017/01/04/rep-lee-zeldin-sworn-second-term/|title=Rep. Lee Zeldin sworn in to second term|date=January 4, 2017|work=riverheadlocal.com|accessdate=January 19, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://thehill.com/new-members-guide-2014/223737-rep-elect-lee-zeldin-r-ny-01|title=Rep.-elect Lee Zeldin (R-N.Y.-01)|first=Ashley|last=Perks|date=November 12, 2014|website=TheHill}}</ref> He was raised in [[Shirley, New York]], and graduated from [[William Floyd High School]] in [[Mastic Beach, New York]], in 1998.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://projects.newsday.com/voters-guide/profile/lee-m-zeldin|title=Lee M. Zeldin {{!}} General Election, November 6, 2018|website=Newsday|language=en|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref> He also attended [[Hebrew school]].<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.haaretz.com/jewish/.premium-lone-republican-jew-in-congress-speaks-up-1.5369091|title=The Lone Republican Jew in Congress: 'Iran Is Playing Our President Like a String Quartet'|date=2015-06-03|work=Haaretz|access-date=2019-10-22|language=en}}</ref> \n\nZeldin received a bachelor's degree in political science from the [[University at Albany, SUNY|University at Albany]] in 2001.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://riverheadlocal.com/2014/11/03/hotly-contested-expensive-bishop-zeldi-congressional-race-draws-to-a-close/|title=Hotly contested \u2014 and very expensive \u2014 congressional race draws to a close|last=Civiletti|first=Denise|date=2014-11-03|website=RiverheadLOCAL|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref> He then earned a [[Juris Doctor]] from [[Albany Law School]] in May 2003.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> In 2004 he was admitted to the [[New York State Bar]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesunion.com/local/article/At-29-Mr-Carlucci-goes-to-Albany-932020.php|title=At 29, Mr. Carlucci goes to Albany|last=writer|first=STEPHANIE LEE Staff|date=2011-01-03|website=Times Union|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n\n== Military service and legal practice ==\n[[File:United States Army Captain Lee Zeldin deployed to Iraq in 2006.jpg|thumb|U.S. Army Captain Lee Zeldin deployed to [[Iraq]] in 2006]]\nZeldin received an [[Army ROTC]] commission as a [[second lieutenant]], and served in the [[United States Army]] from 2003 to 2007,<ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theepochtimes.com/state-sen-lee-zeldin-on-the-radar-list_646929.html|title=State Sen. Lee Zeldin: On the Radar List|date=2014-04-29|website=theepochtimes.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=http://jewishweek.timesofisrael.com/lee-zeldin-what-jew-need-to-know/|title=Lee Zeldin: What Jew Need To Know|last=Kook|first=Elana|website=jewishweek.timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref> first in the [[Military Intelligence Corps]].<ref name=\":4\" /> In summer 2006 he was deployed to [[Tikrit, Iraq]], with an infantry [[battalion]] of [[paratroopers]] from the [[82nd Airborne Division]] in support of [[Operation Iraqi Freedom]]. Zeldin also served as a prosecutor in the [[Judge Advocate General's Corps, United States Army|Judge Advocate General's Corps]] and as a military [[magistrate]].<ref name=\"autogenerated3\">{{cite web|url=https://zeldin.house.gov/about/full-biography|title=Biography|date=December 11, 2012|website=Congressman Lee Zeldin}}</ref> In 2007 he transitioned from active duty to the [[United States Army Reserve|Army Reserve]], where he still serves with the rank of [[lieutenant colonel (United States)|lieutenant colonel]].<ref name=autogenerated3 />\n\nIn 2007 Zeldin became an attorney for the [[Port Authority of New York and New Jersey]].<ref name=\"autogenerated2\">{{cite web|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=Z000017|title=ZELDIN, Lee M - Biographical Information|website=bioguide.congress.gov}}</ref> In 2008 he started a law practice in Smithtown. He operated it full-time until he was elected to [[New York's 3rd State Senate district]] in 2010.<ref name=\"Official bio\">{{cite web|url=https://zeldin.house.gov/about|title=Lee Zeldin|publisher=house.gov|accessdate=February 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==New York Senate==\n\n===Elections===\nIn 2010 Zeldin ran in the [[New York Senate|New York State Senate]]'s 3rd district, challenging [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] incumbent [[Brian X. Foley]]. Zeldin defeated Foley with 58% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|title=New York State Legislature Election 2010|url=http://elections.nytimes.com/2010/results/new-york/state-legislature|work=New York Times|accessdate=April 28, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120615060350/http://elections.nytimes.com/2010/results/new-york/state-legislature|archivedate=June 15, 2012}}</ref> In 2012 he was reelected to a second two-year term, defeating Democrat Francis Genco with 56% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=773927|title=Our Campaigns \u2013 NY State Senate 03 Race|date=November 6, 2012|work=ourcampaigns.com|accessdate=February 20, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nIn January 2011 Zeldin co-sponsored legislation that enacted a 2% [[property tax]] cap.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Civiletti|first1=Denise|title=Hotly contested \u2014 and very expensive \u2014 congressional race draws to a close|url=http://riverheadlocal.com/2014/11/03/hotly-contested-expensive-bishop-zeldi-congressional-race-draws-to-a-close|accessdate=June 20, 2016|publisher=Riverhead Local|date=November 3, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2011 Zeldin voted against the [[Marriage Equality Act (New York)|Marriage Equality Act]], which the Senate passed 33\u201329.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://open.nysenate.gov/legislation/bill/a8354-2011|title=A8354-2011 \u2013 NY Senate Open Legislation \u2013 Enacts the Marriage Equality Act relating to ability of individuals to marry \u2013 New York State Senate|work=nysenate.gov|accessdate=February 20, 2015}}</ref> In a statement after the bill passed, he said: \"It is my belief that marriage should be defined as between a man and a woman.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lavers|first1=Michael|title=Fire Islanders Celebrate Passage of Marriage Equality Bill|url=http://www.edgenewyork.com/news/local/news//122206/fire_islanders_celebrate_passage_of_marriage_equality_bill|accessdate=June 25, 2014|publisher=Fire Island News|date=July 19, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2011 Zeldin supported a $250 million cut to the [[Metropolitan Transportation Authority|MTA]] payroll tax.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hamilton|first1=Colby|title=NY Governor Cuomo Signs MTA Tax Reduction Into Law|url=http://www.wnyc.org/story/283886-ny-governor-cuomo-signs-mta-tax-reduction-into-law|accessdate=June 20, 2016|publisher=WNYC|date=December 12, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Long Island Officials Lobby To Eliminate MTA Payroll Tax|url=http://newyork.cbslocal.com/2012/02/03/long-island-officials-lobby-to-eliminate-mta-payroll-tax|accessdate=June 20, 2016|publisher=CBS New York|date=February 3, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2012 Zeldin created the PFC [[Joseph Patrick Dwyer|Joseph Dwyer]] [[Posttraumatic stress disorder|PTSD]] Peer-to-Peer Veterans Support program as part of the 2012\u201313 New York State Budget.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Fertoli|first1=Annmarie|title=4 New York Counties Set to Receive Funding for Vets Peer Pilot Program|url=http://www.wnyc.org/story/197867-four-new-york-counties-receive-funding-vets-pilot-programs|accessdate=April 28, 2016|publisher=WNYC News|date=April 8, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=LaRocco|first1=Paul|title=Suffolk: Bellone credits Zeldin on state PTSD program|url=http://www.newsday.com/long-island/politics/spin-cycle-1.812042/suffolk-bellone-credits-zeldin-on-state-ptsd-program-1.6250087|accessdate=June 26, 2014|publisher=Newsday|date=October 14, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn January 14, 2013, Zeldin did not vote on the [[NY SAFE Act]], a [[gun control]] bill that passed the New York State Senate, 43 votes to 18.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/bill/15977/42092/110252/establishes-secure-ammunition-and-firearms-enforcement#.U0ymJVcvmSo|title=Project Vote Smart \u2013 The Voter's Self Defense System|work=Project Vote Smart|accessdate=February 20, 2015}}</ref> In a statement released to the press after the vote, he said he would have voted against the measure.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bonner|first1=Ryan|title=Zeldin Releases Statement on Gun Legislation|url=http://patch.com/new-york/patchogue/zeldin-releases-statement-on-gun-legislation|accessdate=September 27, 2016|publisher=Patchogue Patch|date=January 15, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2014 Zeldin introduced a bill that sought to halt implementation of the [[Common Core]] curriculum for three years.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Franchi|first1=Jaime|title=Common Core Adjustments Do Not Go Far Enough, Blast Opponents|url=https://www.longislandpress.com/2014/02/16/common-core-adjustments-do-not-go-far-enough-say-opponents|accessdate=September 27, 2016|publisher=Long Island Press|date=February 16, 2014}}</ref> The bill was referred to the Senate Education Committee.\n\nIn March 2014 Zeldin voted against the New York Dream Act.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://open.nysenate.gov/legislation/bill/A2597A-2013|title=A2597A-2013 \u2013 NY Senate Open Legislation \u2013 Enacts the New York state DREAM ACT; repealer|work=nysenate.gov|accessdate=February 20, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Ramirez|first1=David|title=New York Dream Act Proponents Increase Pressure On Governor Cuomo To Provide Budget Support|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/03/31/dream-act-new-york-cuomo-budget_n_1390326.html|accessdate=June 26, 2014|publisher=Huffington Post|date=March 31, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. Congress==\n===Elections===\n'''2008'''{{See also|2008 United States House of Representatives elections in New York#District 1}}\nIn 2008 Zeldin challenged incumbent Democratic Congressman [[Tim Bishop]] in [[New York's 1st congressional district]]. Bishop defeated Zeldin 58%\u201342%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=389429|title=Our Campaigns \u2013 NY \u2013 District 01 Race|date=November 4, 2008|work=ourcampaigns.com|accessdate=February 20, 2015}}</ref>\n\n'''2014'''{{See also|2014 United States House of Representatives elections in New York#District 1}}\nOn October 6, 2013, Zeldin announced he would again seek the Republican nomination to run against Bishop.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Brand|first1=Rick|title=Zeldin to challenge Bishop for House seat|url=http://www.newsday.com/long-island/suffolk/zeldin-to-challenge-bishop-for-house-seat-1.6208531|accessdate=September 27, 2016|publisher=Newsday|date=October 6, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nysenate.gov/senators/lee-m-zeldin|title=Senator Lee M. Zeldin|date=December 20, 2010|website=NY State Senate}}</ref> He defeated [[George Demos]] in the Republican Party primary,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gannon|first1=Tim|last2=Pinciaro|first2=Joseph|title=Zeldin tops Demos, will face Bishop this fall|url=http://riverheadnewsreview.timesreview.com/2014/06/55552/zeldin-holds-early-lead-in-gop-primary|accessdate=September 27, 2016|publisher=Riverhead News-Review|date=June 24, 2014}}</ref> and ran unopposed for the [[Conservative Party of New York State|Conservative Party]] nomination in the primary on June 24, 2014. On November 4, 2014, Zeldin defeated Bishop with 54% of the vote.<ref>{{cite news|last1=LaRocco|first1=Paul|title=Lee Zeldin Defeats Tim Bishop|url=http://www.newsday.com/long-island/lee-zeldin-defeats-tim-bishop-kathleen-rice-wins-over-bruce-blakeman-for-congress-1.9585683|accessdate=November 10, 2014|agency=Newsday|date=November 5, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://suffolktimes.timesreview.com/2014/11/53586/live-election-results-tonight-for-bishop-zeldin-southold-trustee|title=Zeldin defeats Bishop as Suffolk GOP wins big on Election Day|publisher=The Suffolk Times|date=November 4, 2014|accessdate=February 2, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.elections.ny.gov/NYSBOE/elections/2014/general/2014Congress.pdf|title=Rep. in Congress Election Returns November 4, 2014|publisher=New York State Board of Elections}}</ref>\n\n'''2016'''{{See also|2016 United States House of Representatives elections in New York#District 1}}\nIn February 2015 the [[National Republican Congressional Committee]] announced that Zeldin was one of 12 members in the Patriot Program, a program designed to help protect vulnerable Republican incumbents heading into the 2016 election.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://atr.rollcall.com/nrcc-patriot-program-2016/|title=Exclusive: NRCC Announces 12 Members in Patriot Program|work=Roll Call: At the Races|accessdate=February 5, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Hohmann|first1=James|last2=Viebeck|first2=Elise|title=The Daily 202: Contract with the NRCC \u2014 The deal GOPers make to get reelected|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/powerpost/wp/2015/09/03/the-daily-202-contract-with-the-nrcc-the-deal-gopers-make-to-get-reelected|accessdate=February 5, 2016|work=The Washington Post|date=September 3, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2016 Republican primary, Zeldin faced no opposition. In the November 8 general election, he faced Democrat Anna Throne-Holst, a member of the [[Southampton, New York|Southampton]] Town Board.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Path\u00e9|first1=Simone|title=Throne-Holst Will Challenge New York's Lee Zeldin|url=http://www.rollcall.com/news/politics/democrats-new-york-house-zeldin-throne-holst-calone|accessdate=July 10, 2016|publisher=Roll Call|date=July 8, 2016}}</ref> Zeldin won with 58% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://suffolktimes.timesreview.com/2016/11/71661/live-results-zeldin-throne-holst-election-day-2016-ny-cd-1/|title=On night of Trump win, Zeldin makes history|publisher=|accessdate=November 10, 2016}}</ref> He became the only Jewish Republican in Congress, following Representative [[Eric Cantor]]\u2019s primary defeat.<ref name=autogenerated1 /><ref name=\"autogenerated8\">{{cite web|url=https://www.tabletmag.com/scroll/186851/meet-jewish-republican-congressman-lee-zeldin|title=Meet Lee Zeldin, Jewish Republican Congressman from New York|date=November 5, 2014|website=Tablet Magazine}}</ref>\n\n'''2018'''{{See also|2018 United States House of Representatives elections in New York#District 1}}\nZeldin ran unopposed in the 2018 Republican primary. In the November general election he faced Democratic nominee Perry Gershon and [[Working Families Party]] nominee Patricia Latzman.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.longislandadvance.net/5612/Perry-Gershon-to-face-Congressman-Lee-Zeldin-in-midterms|title=Perry Gershon to face Congressman Lee Zeldin in midterms|last=Smith|first=Tara|date=|work=|access-date=2018-09-11}}</ref> \n\nFor the second consecutive election, Zeldin's campaign sent voters mailers instructing them to postmark their absentee ballots by the wrong date, November 6; the actual deadline was November 5. Zeldin's Democratic opponent Perry Gershon's campaign said the mailers targeted likely Democratic voters, such as college students. Zeldin's campaign said the incorrect date was a mistake and provided a statement from its printer, PDQ Print and Mail, taking responsibility. The campaign said it sent a follow-up mailer with the correct date.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsday.com/long-island/politics/spin-cycle/zeldin-gershon-mailer-1.22304894|title=Zeldin mailer uses wrong deadline for absentees|publisher=|accessdate=November 23, 2018}}</ref> His campaign featured fundraisers with [[Sebastian Gorka]] and [[Breitbart News]] founder [[Steve Bannon]]. At one event, reporters from local news outlets were removed.<ref>{{cite web|url=pcli.org/2018/07/press-club-reacts-to-journalists-removal-from-rep-zeldins-political-rally|title=Press Club reacts to journalists' removal from Rep. Zeldin's political rally|publisher=|accessdate=July 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\nZeldin defeated Gershon 53%\u201347%.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.realclearpolitics.com/epolls/2018/house/ny/new_york_1st_district_zeldin_vs_gershon-6383.html|title=New York 1st District - Zeldin vs. Gershon|work=realclearpolitics.com|accessdate=December 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\n'''Committee assignments'''\n\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs|Committee on Foreign Affairs]]'''\n**[[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on the Middle East and North Africa|Subcommittee on the Middle East and North Africa]]\n**[[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on Terrorism, Nonproliferation, and Trade|Subcommittee on Terrorism, Nonproliferation, and Trade]]\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Financial Services|Committee on Financial Services]]'''\n**[[United States House Financial Services Subcommittee on Housing and Insurance|Subcommittee on Housing and Insurance]]\n**[[United States House Financial Services Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations|Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations]]\n**[[United States House Financial Services Subcommittee on Terrorism and Illicit Finance|Subcommittee on Terrorism and Illicit Finance]]\n\n'''Caucuses'''\n\nZeldin is a member of the [[Climate Solutions Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Climate Solutions Caucus|url=https://citizensclimatelobby.org/climate-solutions-caucus|website=Citizens Climate Lobby|accessdate=August 23, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Smith|first1=Tara|title=Citizens lobby for the environment|url=https://www.longislandadvance.net/4024/Citizens-lobby-for-the-environment|accessdate=September 6, 2017|publisher=The Long Island Advance|date=January 5, 2017}}</ref> and the [[Republican Main Street Partnership]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://republicanmainstreet.org/members/|format=|publisher=Republican Mains Street Partnership|date=|accessdate=4 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180826123025/https://republicanmainstreet.org/members/|archive-date=August 26, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> As of 2017 he was co-chair of the House Republican Israel Caucus.<ref>[https://www.jta.org/2017/06/01/politics/trump-signs-waiver-will-not-move-embassy-to-jerusalem \"Trump signs waiver, won\u2019t move embassy to Jerusalem now,\"] JTA, June 1, 2017.</ref>\n\n==Political positions==\nIn July 2015 Zeldin was among nine Republicans who faced criticism after meeting with [[Oath Keepers]], a group of retired military, police, and fire department employees. ''[[New York Daily News|The New York Daily News]]'' reported that \"the chapter's website includes postings by a member embracing a film that claims the December 2012 [[Sandy Hook Elementary School shooting|Sandy Hook massacre]] was a hoax, and calling President Obama a 'Muslim/Extremist.'\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/politics/rep-hit-meeting-extreme-conservatives-article-1.2281013|title=Long Island Rep. Lee Zeldin among nine Republicans facing attacks for meeting with extremist conservative group|work=New York Daily News}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2016 Zeldin was ranked as the 45th-most bipartisan member of the U.S. House of Representatives during the [[114th United States Congress]] (and the eighth-most-bipartisan member of the U.S. House of Representatives from New York) in the Bipartisan Index created by [[The Lugar Center]] and the [[McCourt School of Public Policy]] that ranks members of the United States Congress by their degree of bipartisanship (by measuring the frequency each member's bills attract co-sponsors from the opposite party, and each member's co-sponsorship of bills by members of the opposite party).<ref>{{Citation|title=The Lugar Center - McCourt School Bipartisan Index|date=March 7, 2016|url=http://www.thelugarcenter.org/assets/htmldocuments/The%20Lugar%20Center%20-%20McCourt%20School%20Bipartisan%20Index%20114th%20Congress%20House%20Scores.pdf|publisher=[[The Lugar Center]]|accessdate=April 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Education===\nIn July 2015 Zeldin attached an amendment to the [[Student Success Act]] to allow states to opt out of [[Common Core State Standards Initiative|Common Core]] without penalty.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.capitalnewyork.com/article/albany/2015/03/8563290/zeldin-begins-anti-common-core-amendment|title=Zeldin begins with an anti-Common Core amendment|accessdate=February 27, 2015|work=Politico New York}}</ref> The amendment was passed and signed into law.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://riverheadlocal.com/2015/12/03/education-bill-with-zeldin-amendment-to-allow-states-to-opt-out-of-common-core-passes-congress|title=Zeldin Anti-Common Core Amendment Passed|date=December 3, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Environment===\n\nIn April 2015, along with Senator [[Charles Schumer]], Zeldin introduced the Fluke Fairness Act. The bill would have changed the current system for managing [[Summer flounder|fluke]] fishing quotas by creating a regional approach to updating quotas and standards based on geographic, scientific, and economic data.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.riverheadlocal.com/2015/04/25/federal-fluke-fairness-act-would-correct-inequitable-treatment-of-l-i-anglers-schumer-zeldin|title=Federal 'Fluke Fairness Act' would correct inequitable treatment of L.I. anglers: Schumer, Zeldin|work=Riverhead Local}}</ref> The bill did not pass.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/114th-congress/senate-bill/1107|title=S.1107 - 114th Congress (2015-2016): Fluke Fairness Act of 2015|last=Charles|first=Schumer|date=2015-04-28|website=congress.gov|language=en|access-date=2018-09-22}}</ref>\n\nOn July 15, 2015, Zeldin introduced the [[Exclusive economic zone|Exclusive Economic Zone]] Clarification Act.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/114th-congress/house-bill/3070|title=H.R.3070|work=congress.gov|accessdate=March 3, 2016}}</ref> The bill proposed to amend the boundary in part of the federal [[Exclusive Economic Zone]] (EEZ). It would give fisheries management of [[Block Island Sound]] exclusively to New York and Rhode Island; some Connecticut fishermen said the bill could put them out of business.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wtnh.com/2016/02/15/proposed-bill-could-put-connecticut-fishermen-out-of-business|title=Bill in Congress could hurt Connecticut fishermen, and fish|accessdate=February 27, 2015|work=WTNH}}{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/wireStory/long-island-sound-discontent-fishing-rights-push-37220874|title=On Long Island Sound, Discord Over Push for Fishing Rights|accessdate=March 3, 2016|work=ABC News}}</ref> The bill died in committee.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/114th-congress/house-bill/3070/text|title=Text - H.R.3070 - 114th Congress (2015-2016): EEZ Transit Zone Clarification and Access Act|last=Lee|first=Zeldin|date=2016-06-08|website=congress.gov|language=en|access-date=2018-09-22}}</ref>\n\nAlso in September 2015, Zeldin, along with [[Citizens Campaign for the Environment]] executive director Adrienne Esposito, condemned a proposed federal plan for dumping of dredged materials, saying, \"We can't just assume that dumping these waste spoils in the [[Long Island Sound]] is environmentally benign.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Blasl|first1=Katie|title=Long Island Sound is 'not a landfill', say environmentalists opposed to open water waste dumping plan|url=http://www.riverheadlocal.com/2015/09/17/long-island-sound-is-not-a-landfill-say-environmentalists-opposed-to-open-water-waste-dumping-plan|accessdate=March 3, 2016|publisher=Riverhead Local|date=September 17, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Rep. Zeldin joins call to halt Sound dumping|url=http://longisland.news12.com/news/rep-zeldin-joins-call-to-halt-dredged-sediment-dumping-in-long-island-sound-1.10852637|accessdate=March 3, 2016|publisher=News12 LongIsland|date=September 16, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018 Zeldin said he did not support the [[Paris Agreement|Paris Accords]] in their form at that time. He expressed concern about \u201cother countries that are contributing to very adverse impacts on our climate but not having the level of responsibility that they need to have in stepping up and making a positive change in their own countries.\u201d<ref>[https://www.bloomberg.com/news/videos/2018-04-25/rep-zeldin-says-u-s-should-be-willing-to-decertify-iran-deal-video Rep. Zeldin Says U.S. Should Be Willing to Decertify Iran Deal] Bloomberg April 25, 2018</ref>\n\n===Foreign affairs===\nIn July 2016 Zeldin criticized [[Barack Obama|President Obama]]'s [[Iran nuclear deal framework|Iran Nuclear Deal]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newsday.com/long-island/lee-zeldin-steve-israel-reject-and-are-skeptical-of-iran-nuclear-deal-1.10640589|title=Republicans denounce Iran deal; Democrats respond cautiously|last1=Brune|first1=Tom|date=July 14, 2015|accessdate=June 20, 2016|publisher=Newsday}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2016 the ''[[New York Post]]'' reported that Zeldin was a no-show in 2015 at 12 of 18 [[United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs|House Committee on Foreign Affairs]] hearings that dealt specifically with [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|ISIL]] and with [[Syria]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2016/01/14/tough-talking-freshman-congressman-has-been-blowing-off-work|title=Tough-talking freshman congressman has been skipping Foreign Affairs Committee meetings|work=New York Post|accessdate=January 31, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsday.com/long-island/politics/spin-cycle/rep-lee-zeldin-s-hearing-absences-draw-fire-from-rivals-1.11347327?pts=474522|title=Rep. Lee Zeldin's hearing absences draw fire from rivals|work=Newsday|accessdate=January 31, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2016, along with Representatives [[Mike Pompeo]] of [[Kansas]] and [[Frank LoBiondo]] of [[New Jersey]], Zeldin sought visas to travel to [[Iran]] to check the country's compliance with the [[Iran nuclear deal framework]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Brune|first1=Tom|title=Rep. Lee Zeldin seeks Iran visa to check on nuke compliance|url=http://www.newsday.com/long-island/rep-lee-zeldin-seeks-iran-visa-to-check-on-nuke-compliance-1.11430362|accessdate=February 26, 2016|publisher=Newsday|date=February 4, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Nicholas|first1=Elizabeth|title=Meeting the Tea Party in Tehran|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/elizabeth-nicholas/meeting-the-tea-party-in-_b_9311336.html|accessdate=February 27, 2016|publisher=Huffington Post|date=February 25, 2016}}</ref> In June Iran called the request a \"publicity stunt\" and said it would deny the visas.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Vahdat|first1=Amir|title=Iran says US congressmen can't visit amid nuclear deal row|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/24bf91854009440cb610828c1d5a38dd/iran-says-us-congressmen-cant-visit-amid-nuclear-deal-row|accessdate=June 16, 2016|work=Associated Press|date=June 7, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Health care===\nIn May 2015 Zeldin voted for H.R.36, a bill he co-sponsored, which would prohibit abortions in cases where the probable age of the [[fetus]] is 20 weeks or later, and would impose criminal penalties on doctors who violate the ban.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsday.com/long-island/politics/spin-cycle/emily-s-list-declares-rep-zeldin-on-notice-for-2016-1.10496400|title=Emily's List Declares Rep Zeldin On Notice for 2016|work=Newsday}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015 Zeldin co-sponsored two bills in Congress to combat [[Lyme disease]], the Tick-Borne Disease Research and Accountability and Transparency Act of 2015<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/114th-congress/house-bill/789/cosponsors|title=H.R.789|work=congress.gov|accessdate=March 2, 2016}}</ref> and the [[21st Century Cures Act]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/114th-congress/house-bill/6/cosponsors|title=H.R.6|work=congress.gov|accessdate=March 2, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://suffolktimes.timesreview.com/2015/09/62315/grossman-column-time-to-legislate-against-lyme-disease|title=Grossman Column: Time to legislate against Lyme disease|date=September 20, 2015|publisher=The Suffolk Times|last1=Grossman|first1=Karl|accessdate=March 2, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn September 18, 2015, Zeldin voted for the Defund Planned Parenthood Act of 2015,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/114th-congress/house-bill/3134|title=H.R.3134|work=congress.gov|accessdate=March 2, 2016}}</ref> a bill that would defund [[Planned Parenthood]] for one year unless the organization agreed not to provide abortion services.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Harding|first1=Robert|title=HOW THEY VOTED: House passes bill to defund Planned Parenthood; Katko, Hanna split on vote|url=http://auburnpub.com/blogs/eye_on_ny/how-they-voted-house-passes-bill-to-defund-planned-parenthood/article_d48b67aa-5e25-11e5-917b-e3315121bff3.html|accessdate=March 2, 2016|publisher=The Citizen (Auburn New York)|date=September 19, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Merrill|first1=Kitty|title=Throne-Holst On The Offensive|url=http://www.indyeastend.com/Articles-News-i-2015-09-23-120005.113117-ThroneHolst-On-The-Offensive.html|accessdate=March 2, 2016|publisher=The Independent|date=September 23, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn May 4, 2017, Zeldin voted in favor of repealing the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]] (Obamacare) and passing the [[American Health Care Act of 2017|American Health Care Act]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.longislandadvance.net/4419/Zeldin-votes-to-repeal-Affordable-Care-Act|title=Zeldin votes to repeal Affordable Care Act|last1=Smith|first1=Tara|date=May 11, 2017|accessdate=May 15, 2017|publisher=Long Island Advance}}</ref><ref name=\":02\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/graphics/politics/ahca-house-vote|title=How the House voted to pass the GOP health-care bill|website=Washington Post|access-date=2017-05-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/05/04/politics/house-health-care-vote/index.html|title=How every member voted on health care bill|last=Staff|first=C.N.N.|website=CNN|accessdate=2017-05-04}}</ref>\n\n===Israel===\nZeldin has said that Israel is \u201cAmerica\u2019s strongest ally\" and that Congress must \u201cprotect Israel\u2019s right to self-defense.\u201d<ref name=\":5\" /> In 2016 he spoke in support of the anti-[[Boycott, Divestment and Sanctions]] (BDS) legislation that passed the [[New York State Senate]]. In March 2017 he co-sponsored a bipartisan bill in the House of Representatives, the Israel Anti-Boycott Act, to oppose boycotts of Israel and \u201cto further combat the anti-Israel boycott, divestment and sanctions (BDS) movement.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thetower.org/4773-bipartisan-bill-against-israel-boycotts-introduced-in-house-of-representatives/|title=Bipartisan Bill Against Israel Boycotts Introduced in House of Representatives|date=March 24, 2017|website=The Tower}}</ref>  He supported the Trump administration's decision to relocate the U.S. Embassy in Israel from Tel Aviv to Jerusalem in May 2018 as part of the [[United States recognition of Jerusalem as capital of Israel]].<ref>[http://www.27east.com/news/article.cfm/East-End/556348/Congressman-Lee-Zeldin-Attends-Opening-Of-US-Embassy-In-Israell Congressman Lee Zeldin Attends Opening Of U.S. Embassy In Israel]</ref>\n\n===Land management===\nIn April 2016 Zeldin introduced legislation to prevent the federal government's sale of [[Plum Island (New York)|Plum Island]] to the highest bidder.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Finn|first1=Lisa|title=Rep. Lee Zeldin on Battle to Preserve Plum Island: 'Losing's Not An Option'|url=http://patch.com/new-york/northfork/rep-lee-zeldin-battle-preserve-plum-island-losings-not-option|accessdate=April 28, 2016|publisher=North Fork Patch|date=April 24, 2016}}</ref> In May 2016 his bill unanimously passed the House.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Irizarry|first1=Lisa|title=Plum Island protection bill passed by House|url=http://www.newsday.com/long-island/suffolk/lee-zeldin-s-plum-island-bill-scheduled-for-house-vote-1.11802207|accessdate=May 17, 2016|publisher=Newsday|date=May 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== LGBT rights ===\n\nAs a New York state senator in 2011, Zeldin voted against the [[Marriage Equality Act (New York)|Marriage Equality Act]], which legalized same-sex marriage in the state.<ref>{{cite web |title=Assembly Bill A8354 |url=https://www.nysenate.gov/legislation/bills/2011/A8354 |website=The New York State Senate |accessdate=May 3, 2019}}</ref> In June 2015, after the [[Supreme Court of the United States|United States Supreme Court]] ruled in ''[[Obergefell v. Hodges]]'' that state-level bans on [[same-sex marriage]] were unconstitutional, Zeldin would not comment about his view of same-sex marriage, but indicated that he believed the issue should have been decided at the state level.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.27east.com/news/article.cfm/Water-Mill/112053/Supreme-Court-Ruling-Legalizes-Gay-Marriage-Bridgehampton-Ceremony-At-Center-Of-Case|title=Supreme Court Ruling Legalizes Gay Marriage; Bridgehampton Ceremony Was At Center Of Case|work=27east.com|accessdate=February 27, 2015}}</ref> A month later he signed on as a co-sponsor of the [[First Amendment Defense Act]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/114th-congress/house-bill/2802/cosponsors|title=HR 2802|work=congress.gov|accessdate=February 27, 2016}}</ref> a bill whose supporters said was designed to protect Americans who used their religious beliefs to deny services to same sex couples or unmarried pregnant women. Critics of the measure said it would enable people to violate the legal rights of same-sex couples and their children by discriminating against them.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lgbtweekly.com/2015/06/20/hrc-first-amendment-defense-act-is-reckless/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150725112902/http://lgbtweekly.com/2015/06/20/hrc-first-amendment-defense-act-is-reckless/|archivedate=2015-07-25|title=HRC: First Amendment Defense Act is 'reckless'|last1=Lee|first1=Steve|date=June 20, 2015|publisher=San Diego LGBT Weekly (San Diego California)|accessdate=October 25, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/first-amendment-defense-act_55a7ffe6e4b04740a3df4ca1|title=First Amendment Defense Act|work=huffingtonpost.com|accessdate=October 25, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://dyn.realclearpolitics.com/congressional_bill_tracker/bill/114/hr2802|title=H.R. 2802: First Amendment Defense Act|work=RealClearPolitics.com|accessdate=March 2, 2016}}</ref> In May 2019, Zeldin voted against the [[Equality Act (United States)|Equality Act]].<ref>[https://www.congress.gov/bill/116th-congress/house-bill/5 H.R. 5]</ref><ref>[http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2019/roll217.xml|FINAL VOTE RESULTS FOR ROLL CALL 217]</ref><ref>[https://thinkprogress.org/25-equality-act-opponents-from-states-with-lgbtq-non-discrimination-protections-8fba0c05e4f7/ These 25 Republicans should have known better about the Equality Act]</ref>\n\n=== Taxes ===\n\nIn November 2017 Zeldin said he was not yet satisfied with the proposed Republican tax bill. He complained in particular about the elimination of the state and local tax deduction. That same month House Speaker [[Paul D. Ryan]] canceled plans to attend a fundraiser for Zeldin after Zeldin voted against the House version of the bill.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/29/nyregion/ryan-fundraiser-zeldin-tax-bill.html|title=Paul Ryan Cancels Fund-Raiser for Lee Zeldin Over Tax Bill Vote|last=Goldmacher|first=Shane|date=November 29, 2017|work=New York Times|access-date=September 5, 2018|language=en}}</ref> In December Zeldin called the tax bill \u201ca geographic redistribution of wealth\u201d that takes money from some states while providing [[tax relief]] to others. He suggested that the removal of the [[state tax]] deduction could have been implemented gradually.<ref>[https://www.npr.org/2017/11/03/561781225/republican-rep-lee-zeldin-on-his-opposition-to-gop-tax-bill?t=1533140083378 Republican Rep. Lee Zeldin On His Opposition To GOP Tax Bill] NPR November 3, 2017</ref><ref>[https://www.cnbc.com/2017/12/20/gop-rep-lee-zeldin-tax-bill-a-geographic-redistribution-of-wealth.html GOP congressman votes 'no' on tax bill, calls it a 'geographic redistribution of wealth'] Michelle Fox; CNBC; December 20, 2017</ref>\n\nZeldin voted against the [[Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017]], which passed in December 2017.<ref name=\"Almukhtar122117\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/12/19/us/politics/tax-bill-house-live-vote.html?_r=0|title=How Each House Member Voted on the Tax Bill|last1=Almukhtar|first1=Sarah|date=19 December 2017|website=The New York Times|accessdate=21 December 2017}}</ref> He supported the [[corporate tax]] cuts in the bill but did not approve of the limit for [[property tax]] deductions, preferring a cap of $20,000 or $25,000 as opposed to the $10,000 that was in the bill.<ref name=\"yahoo122117\">{{cite web|url=https://uk.finance.yahoo.com/news/gop-congressman-votes-apos-no-201200326.html|title=GOP congressman votes 'no' on tax bill, calls it a 'geographic redistribution of wealth'|website=Yahoo! Finance|accessdate=21 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Trump administration ===\nOn May 3, 2016, Zeldin endorsed [[Donald Trump]] as the Republican presidential nominee.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Brune|first1=Tom|title=Reps. Peter King, Lee Zeldin endorse Donald Trump for president|url=http://www.newsday.com/long-island/politics/spin-cycle/reps-peter-king-lee-zeldin-endorse-donald-trump-for-president-1.11762295|accessdate=August 15, 2016|publisher=Newsday|date=May 4, 2016}}</ref> Zeldin had previously indicated that he would support the eventual Republican nominee.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Clancy|first1=Ambrose|title=Zeldin will support whoever GOP nominates|url=http://suffolktimes.timesreview.com/2016/03/66217/zeldin-will-support-republican-presidential-nominee-even-trump|accessdate=August 15, 2016|publisher=Suffolk Times|date=March 3, 2016}}</ref> During the campaign, Zeldin faulted Trump for a comment about [[Khizr and Ghazala Khan]], a [[Gold Star family]] whose son Humayun, a [[Captain (United States)|Captain]] in the [[United States Army|Army]], was killed during the [[Iraq War]], but stated he would continue to support Trump.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Brune|first1=Tom|title=Peter King, Lee Zeldin fault Donald Trump for dispute with Khans|url=http://www.newsday.com/long-island/politics/spin-cycle/peter-king-lee-zeldin-fault-donald-trump-for-dispute-with-khans-1.12125170?pts=787531|publisher=Newsday|date=August 2, 2016|accessdate=August 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017 Zeldin supported Trump's [[Dismissal of James Comey|firing of FBI Director James Comey]], saying it offered the [[FBI]] a chance at a \"fresh start\" to rebuild trust.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.newsday.com/long-island/politics/comey-s-firing-spurs-call-for-russia-probe-special-prosecutor-1.13589403|title=With Comey out, Schumer urges special prosecutor|work=Newsday|access-date=2017-05-10}}</ref> In May 2018 Zeldin called for the criminal prosecution of former FBI deputy director [[Andrew McCabe]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/389036-watch-ny-republican-wants-mccabe-prosecuted|title=WATCH: NY Republican wants McCabe prosecuted|last=Hooper|first=Molly K.|date=2018-05-23|work=TheHill|access-date=2018-05-23|language=en}}</ref> Also that month Zeldin called for creating a [[special counsel]] investigation into the FBI and the [[United States Department of Justice|DOJ]] regarding their investigations into [[Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/policy/national-security/388798-house-conservatives-introduce-resolution-calling-for-second-special|title=House conservatives introduce resolution calling for second special counsel|last=Beavers|first=Olivia|date=2018-05-22|work=TheHill|access-date=2018-05-23|language=en}}</ref> Zeldin said the investigations were launched with \"insufficient intelligence and biased motivations\", with surveillance warrants for Trump campaign staffers obtained in \"deeply flawed and questionable\" ways.<ref name=\":1\" /> He also called for an investigation into the FBI's decision to conclude its investigation into the [[Hillary Clinton email controversy]].<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2018/05/22/politics/republicans-house-second-special-counsel-proposal/index.html|title=Republicans renew push for second special counsel|author1=Jeremy Herb |author2=Daniella Diaz|work=CNN|access-date=2018-05-23}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2018\u201319 United States federal government shutdown]] Zeldin voted with the Republican caucus against the controversial appropriations measure to fund the federal government. He instructed the House to withhold his pay until the shutdown ended, saying: \u201cIt\u2019s crazy to me that members of Congress get paid while other federal employees do not.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|last=Civiletti|first=Denise|url=https://riverheadlocal.com/2019/01/04/in-the-new-minority-rep-lee-zeldins-first-day-of-his-third-term-in-congress/|title=In the new minority: Rep. Lee Zeldin's first day of his third term in Congress|work=riverheadlocal.com|date= January 4, 2019|accessdate=January 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\nZeldin defended Trump amid the [[Trump\u2013Ukraine scandal]], which set off an impeachment inquiry against Trump over his request that Ukrainian President [[Volodymyr Zelensky]] investigate Democratic presidential candidate Joe Biden and his son Hunter Biden. Zeldin said in October 2019, \"It is crystal clear... that any allegation that President Trump was trying to get President Zelensky to manufacture dirt on the Bidens is just not true\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afp.com/en/news/15/intel-official-testify-new-texts-pile-pressure-trump-doc-1l13hu5|title=Intel official to testify as new texts pile pressure on Trump|website=AFP.com|language=en|access-date=2019-10-04}}</ref>\n\nZeldin has become one of Trump's staunchest defenders during his public impeachment hearings. In the seven impeachment deposition transcripts released so far, no Republican has spoken more than Zeldin, who is referenced more than 550 times.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/trump-impeachment-inquiry/trump-s-defender-how-little-known-gop-lawmaker-became-point-n1076046|title=How a little-known GOP lawmaker became a point man in Trump's impeachment defense|website=NBC News|language=en|access-date=2019-11-11}}</ref>\n\n===Veterans affairs===\nIn February 2015 Zeldin introduced his first bill, to eliminate the dollar limit for loans that the [[United States Department of Veterans Affairs]] can guarantee for a veteran.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newsday.com/long-island/politics/spin-cycle/rice-and-zeldin-file-first-bills-aimed-at-aiding-vets-1.10068978|title=Rice, Zeldin file first bills aimed at aiding vets|accessdate=February 5, 2016|publisher=Newsday}}</ref> In February 2016 he proposed federal legislation to fund a three-year, $25-million nationwide veterans' peer-support program modeled on one he helped establish while a member of the New York State Senate.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newsday.com/long-island/politics/lee-zeldin-proposes-25m-veterans-counseling-program-1.11469897|title=Lee Zeldin proposes $25M veterans counseling program|last1=Evans|first1=Martin|date=February 14, 2016|accessdate=February 26, 2016|publisher=Newsday}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nZeldin is Jewish,<ref name=\"Printing2016\">{{cite book|author=Congress (U S ) Joint Committee on Printing|title=Official Congressional Directory 114th Congress, 2015-2016, Convened January 2015|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=W4Som-OxRt4C&pg=PA180|date=30 March 2016|publisher=Government Printing Office|isbn=978-0-16-092997-7|pages=180\u2013}}</ref> and his wife, Diana, is Mormon.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ain|first1=Stewart|title=L.I.'s Zeldin Stepping Into GOP Minefield|url=http://jewishweek.timesofisrael.com/l-i-s-zeldin-stepping-into-gop-minefield|accessdate=July 5, 2018|publisher=The New York Jewish Week|date=November 12, 2014}}</ref> The couple has identical twin daughters, Mikayla and Arianna.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gonzales|first1=Nathan|title=Washington Is a Matter of Life and Death to Congressional Candidate|url=https://www.rollcall.com/news/washington-is-a-matter-of-life-and-death-to-congressional-candidate|accessdate=February 26, 2016|publisher=Roll Call|date=January 24, 2014}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated1 /> They live in [[Shirley, New York]].<ref name=\"Official bio\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Jewish members of the United States Congress]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{commonscat}}\n* [https://zeldin.house.gov/ Congressman Lee Zeldin] official U.S. House site\n* [https://zeldinforcongress.com// Zeldin for Congress] official campaign site\n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/New_York/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Lee_Zeldin_%5BR-1%5D}}\n{{ CongLinks | congbio = Z000017 | fec = H8NY01148 | votesmart = 110252| congress = lee-zeldin/Z000017}}\t\t\n* {{C-SPAN|leezeldin}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-ny-sen}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Brian X. Foley]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[New York State Senate|New York Senate]]<br>from the 3rd district|years=2011\u20132013}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Thomas Croci]]}}\n|-\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{US House succession box\n|before   = [[Tim Bishop]]\n|state    = New York\n|district = 1\n|years    = 2015\u2013present}}\n|-\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Bruce Westerman]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Seniority in the United States House of Representatives|United States Representatives by seniority]]|years=279th}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Trent Kelly]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{USCongRep-start|congresses= 114th-116th [[United States Congress]] |state=[[United States congressional delegations from New York|New York]]}}\n{{USCongRep/NY/114}}\n{{USCongRep/NY/115}}\n{{USCongRep/NY/116}}\n{{USCongRep-end}}\n{{NY-FedRep}}\n{{USHouseCurrent}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zeldin, Lee}}\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Albany Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Jewish American military personnel]]\n[[Category:American army personnel of the Iraq War]]\n[[Category:Jewish members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Republicans]]\n[[Category:New York (state) lawyers]]\n[[Category:New York state senators]]\n[[Category:People from Shirley, New York]]\n[[Category:Republican Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:United States Army officers]]\n", "text_old": "{{COI|date=September 2018}}\n{{short description|U.S. Representative from New York}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name          = Lee Zeldin\n|image         = Lee Zeldin new official portrait.jpg\n|state         = [[New York (state)|New York]]\n|district      = {{ushr|NY|1|1st}}\n|term_start    = January 3, 2015\n|term_end      = \n|predecessor   = [[Tim Bishop]]\n|successor     = \n|state_senate1 = New York State\n|district1     = [[New York's 3rd State Senate district|3rd]]\n|term_start1   = January 1, 2011\n|term_end1     = December 31, 2014\n|predecessor1  = [[Brian X. Foley]]\n|successor1    = [[Thomas Croci]]\n|birth_name    = Lee Michael Zeldin\n|birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1980|1|30}}\n|birth_place   = [[East Meadow, New York]], U.S.\n|death_date    = \n|death_place   = \n|party         = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse        = Diana Zeldin\n|children      = 2\n|education     = [[University at Albany, SUNY|State University of New York, Albany]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[Albany Law School]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n|signature     = Lee Zeldin's Signature.png\n|website       = {{url|zeldin.house.gov|House website}}\n|allegiance    = {{flag|United States}}\n|branch        = {{army|United States}}\n|serviceyears  = 2003\u2013present\n|rank          = [[File:US-O5 insignia.svg|15px]] [[Lieutenant colonel (United States)|Lieutenant Colonel]]\n|battles       = [[Iraq War]]\n}}\n'''Lee Michael Zeldin''' (born January 30, 1980) is an American attorney and politician serving as the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|NY|1}} since 2015. The district includes central and eastern [[Suffolk County, New York]], including most of [[Smithtown, New York|Smithtown]], as well as the towns of [[Brookhaven, New York|Brookhaven]], [[Riverhead (town), New York|Riverhead]], [[Southold, New York|Southold]], [[Southampton (town), New York|Southampton]], [[East Hampton (town), New York|East Hampton]] and [[Shelter Island (town), New York|Shelter Island, New York]]. A member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]], Zeldin previously served as the [[New York State Senate|New York State Senator]] from the [[New York's 3rd State Senate district|3rd district]] from 2011 to 2014.\n\n==Early life and education==\nZeldin was born in [[East Meadow, New York]], the son of Merrill Schwartz and David Zeldin.<ref>{{cite web|last=Civiletti|first=Denise|url=https://riverheadlocal.com/2017/01/04/rep-lee-zeldin-sworn-second-term/|title=Rep. Lee Zeldin sworn in to second term|date=January 4, 2017|work=riverheadlocal.com|accessdate=January 19, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://thehill.com/new-members-guide-2014/223737-rep-elect-lee-zeldin-r-ny-01|title=Rep.-elect Lee Zeldin (R-N.Y.-01)|first=Ashley|last=Perks|date=November 12, 2014|website=TheHill}}</ref> He was raised in [[Shirley, New York]], and graduated from [[William Floyd High School]] in [[Mastic Beach, New York]], in 1998.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://projects.newsday.com/voters-guide/profile/lee-m-zeldin|title=Lee M. Zeldin {{!}} General Election, November 6, 2018|website=Newsday|language=en|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref> He also attended [[Hebrew school]].<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.haaretz.com/jewish/.premium-lone-republican-jew-in-congress-speaks-up-1.5369091|title=The Lone Republican Jew in Congress: 'Iran Is Playing Our President Like a String Quartet'|date=2015-06-03|work=Haaretz|access-date=2019-10-22|language=en}}</ref> \n\nZeldin received a bachelor's degree in political science from the [[University at Albany, SUNY|University at Albany]] in 2001.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://riverheadlocal.com/2014/11/03/hotly-contested-expensive-bishop-zeldi-congressional-race-draws-to-a-close/|title=Hotly contested \u2014 and very expensive \u2014 congressional race draws to a close|last=Civiletti|first=Denise|date=2014-11-03|website=RiverheadLOCAL|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref> He then earned a [[Juris Doctor]] from [[Albany Law School]] in May 2003.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> In 2004 he was admitted to the [[New York State Bar]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesunion.com/local/article/At-29-Mr-Carlucci-goes-to-Albany-932020.php|title=At 29, Mr. Carlucci goes to Albany|last=writer|first=STEPHANIE LEE Staff|date=2011-01-03|website=Times Union|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n\n== Military service and legal practice ==\n[[File:United States Army Captain Lee Zeldin deployed to Iraq in 2006.jpg|thumb|U.S. Army Captain Lee Zeldin deployed to [[Iraq]] in 2006]]\nZeldin received an [[Army ROTC]] commission as a [[second lieutenant]], and served in the [[United States Army]] from 2003 to 2007,<ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theepochtimes.com/state-sen-lee-zeldin-on-the-radar-list_646929.html|title=State Sen. Lee Zeldin: On the Radar List|date=2014-04-29|website=theepochtimes.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=http://jewishweek.timesofisrael.com/lee-zeldin-what-jew-need-to-know/|title=Lee Zeldin: What Jew Need To Know|last=Kook|first=Elana|website=jewishweek.timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref> first in the [[Military Intelligence Corps]].<ref name=\":4\" /> In summer 2006 he was deployed to [[Tikrit, Iraq]], with an infantry [[battalion]] of [[paratroopers]] from the [[82nd Airborne Division]] in support of [[Operation Iraqi Freedom]]. Zeldin also served as a prosecutor in the [[Judge Advocate General's Corps, United States Army|Judge Advocate General's Corps]] and as a military [[magistrate]].<ref name=\"autogenerated3\">{{cite web|url=https://zeldin.house.gov/about/full-biography|title=Biography|date=December 11, 2012|website=Congressman Lee Zeldin}}</ref> In 2007 he transitioned from active duty to the [[United States Army Reserve|Army Reserve]], where he still serves with the rank of [[lieutenant colonel (United States)|lieutenant colonel]].<ref name=autogenerated3 />\n\nIn 2007 Zeldin became an attorney for the [[Port Authority of New York and New Jersey]].<ref name=\"autogenerated2\">{{cite web|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=Z000017|title=ZELDIN, Lee M - Biographical Information|website=bioguide.congress.gov}}</ref> In 2008 he started a law practice in Smithtown. He operated it full-time until he was elected to [[New York's 3rd State Senate district]] in 2010.<ref name=\"Official bio\">{{cite web|url=https://zeldin.house.gov/about|title=Lee Zeldin|publisher=house.gov|accessdate=February 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==New York Senate==\n\n===Elections===\nIn 2010 Zeldin ran in the [[New York Senate|New York State Senate]]'s 3rd district, challenging [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] incumbent [[Brian X. Foley]]. Zeldin defeated Foley with 58% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|title=New York State Legislature Election 2010|url=http://elections.nytimes.com/2010/results/new-york/state-legislature|work=New York Times|accessdate=April 28, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120615060350/http://elections.nytimes.com/2010/results/new-york/state-legislature|archivedate=June 15, 2012}}</ref> In 2012 he was reelected to a second two-year term, defeating Democrat Francis Genco with 56% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=773927|title=Our Campaigns \u2013 NY State Senate 03 Race|date=November 6, 2012|work=ourcampaigns.com|accessdate=February 20, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nIn January 2011 Zeldin co-sponsored legislation that enacted a 2% [[property tax]] cap.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Civiletti|first1=Denise|title=Hotly contested \u2014 and very expensive \u2014 congressional race draws to a close|url=http://riverheadlocal.com/2014/11/03/hotly-contested-expensive-bishop-zeldi-congressional-race-draws-to-a-close|accessdate=June 20, 2016|publisher=Riverhead Local|date=November 3, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2011 Zeldin voted against the [[Marriage Equality Act (New York)|Marriage Equality Act]], which the Senate passed 33\u201329.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://open.nysenate.gov/legislation/bill/a8354-2011|title=A8354-2011 \u2013 NY Senate Open Legislation \u2013 Enacts the Marriage Equality Act relating to ability of individuals to marry \u2013 New York State Senate|work=nysenate.gov|accessdate=February 20, 2015}}</ref> In a statement after the bill passed, he said: \"It is my belief that marriage should be defined as between a man and a woman.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lavers|first1=Michael|title=Fire Islanders Celebrate Passage of Marriage Equality Bill|url=http://www.edgenewyork.com/news/local/news//122206/fire_islanders_celebrate_passage_of_marriage_equality_bill|accessdate=June 25, 2014|publisher=Fire Island News|date=July 19, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2011 Zeldin supported a $250 million cut to the [[Metropolitan Transportation Authority|MTA]] payroll tax.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hamilton|first1=Colby|title=NY Governor Cuomo Signs MTA Tax Reduction Into Law|url=http://www.wnyc.org/story/283886-ny-governor-cuomo-signs-mta-tax-reduction-into-law|accessdate=June 20, 2016|publisher=WNYC|date=December 12, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Long Island Officials Lobby To Eliminate MTA Payroll Tax|url=http://newyork.cbslocal.com/2012/02/03/long-island-officials-lobby-to-eliminate-mta-payroll-tax|accessdate=June 20, 2016|publisher=CBS New York|date=February 3, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2012 Zeldin created the PFC [[Joseph Patrick Dwyer|Joseph Dwyer]] [[Posttraumatic stress disorder|PTSD]] Peer-to-Peer Veterans Support program as part of the 2012\u201313 New York State Budget.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Fertoli|first1=Annmarie|title=4 New York Counties Set to Receive Funding for Vets Peer Pilot Program|url=http://www.wnyc.org/story/197867-four-new-york-counties-receive-funding-vets-pilot-programs|accessdate=April 28, 2016|publisher=WNYC News|date=April 8, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=LaRocco|first1=Paul|title=Suffolk: Bellone credits Zeldin on state PTSD program|url=http://www.newsday.com/long-island/politics/spin-cycle-1.812042/suffolk-bellone-credits-zeldin-on-state-ptsd-program-1.6250087|accessdate=June 26, 2014|publisher=Newsday|date=October 14, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn January 14, 2013, Zeldin did not vote on the [[NY SAFE Act]], a [[gun control]] bill that passed the New York State Senate, 43 votes to 18.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/bill/15977/42092/110252/establishes-secure-ammunition-and-firearms-enforcement#.U0ymJVcvmSo|title=Project Vote Smart \u2013 The Voter's Self Defense System|work=Project Vote Smart|accessdate=February 20, 2015}}</ref> In a statement released to the press after the vote, he said he would have voted against the measure.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bonner|first1=Ryan|title=Zeldin Releases Statement on Gun Legislation|url=http://patch.com/new-york/patchogue/zeldin-releases-statement-on-gun-legislation|accessdate=September 27, 2016|publisher=Patchogue Patch|date=January 15, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2014 Zeldin introduced a bill that sought to halt implementation of the [[Common Core]] curriculum for three years.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Franchi|first1=Jaime|title=Common Core Adjustments Do Not Go Far Enough, Blast Opponents|url=https://www.longislandpress.com/2014/02/16/common-core-adjustments-do-not-go-far-enough-say-opponents|accessdate=September 27, 2016|publisher=Long Island Press|date=February 16, 2014}}</ref> The bill was referred to the Senate Education Committee.\n\nIn March 2014 Zeldin voted against the New York Dream Act.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://open.nysenate.gov/legislation/bill/A2597A-2013|title=A2597A-2013 \u2013 NY Senate Open Legislation \u2013 Enacts the New York state DREAM ACT; repealer|work=nysenate.gov|accessdate=February 20, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Ramirez|first1=David|title=New York Dream Act Proponents Increase Pressure On Governor Cuomo To Provide Budget Support|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/03/31/dream-act-new-york-cuomo-budget_n_1390326.html|accessdate=June 26, 2014|publisher=Huffington Post|date=March 31, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. Congress==\n===Elections===\n'''2008'''{{See also|2008 United States House of Representatives elections in New York#District 1}}\nIn 2008 Zeldin challenged incumbent Democratic Congressman [[Tim Bishop]] in [[New York's 1st congressional district]]. Bishop defeated Zeldin 58%\u201342%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=389429|title=Our Campaigns \u2013 NY \u2013 District 01 Race|date=November 4, 2008|work=ourcampaigns.com|accessdate=February 20, 2015}}</ref>\n\n'''2014'''{{See also|2014 United States House of Representatives elections in New York#District 1}}\nOn October 6, 2013, Zeldin announced he would again seek the Republican nomination to run against Bishop.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Brand|first1=Rick|title=Zeldin to challenge Bishop for House seat|url=http://www.newsday.com/long-island/suffolk/zeldin-to-challenge-bishop-for-house-seat-1.6208531|accessdate=September 27, 2016|publisher=Newsday|date=October 6, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nysenate.gov/senators/lee-m-zeldin|title=Senator Lee M. Zeldin|date=December 20, 2010|website=NY State Senate}}</ref> He defeated [[George Demos]] in the Republican Party primary,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gannon|first1=Tim|last2=Pinciaro|first2=Joseph|title=Zeldin tops Demos, will face Bishop this fall|url=http://riverheadnewsreview.timesreview.com/2014/06/55552/zeldin-holds-early-lead-in-gop-primary|accessdate=September 27, 2016|publisher=Riverhead News-Review|date=June 24, 2014}}</ref> and ran unopposed for the [[Conservative Party of New York State|Conservative Party]] nomination in the primary on June 24, 2014. On November 4, 2014, Zeldin defeated Bishop with 54% of the vote.<ref>{{cite news|last1=LaRocco|first1=Paul|title=Lee Zeldin Defeats Tim Bishop|url=http://www.newsday.com/long-island/lee-zeldin-defeats-tim-bishop-kathleen-rice-wins-over-bruce-blakeman-for-congress-1.9585683|accessdate=November 10, 2014|agency=Newsday|date=November 5, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://suffolktimes.timesreview.com/2014/11/53586/live-election-results-tonight-for-bishop-zeldin-southold-trustee|title=Zeldin defeats Bishop as Suffolk GOP wins big on Election Day|publisher=The Suffolk Times|date=November 4, 2014|accessdate=February 2, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.elections.ny.gov/NYSBOE/elections/2014/general/2014Congress.pdf|title=Rep. in Congress Election Returns November 4, 2014|publisher=New York State Board of Elections}}</ref>\n\n'''2016'''{{See also|2016 United States House of Representatives elections in New York#District 1}}\nIn February 2015 the [[National Republican Congressional Committee]] announced that Zeldin was one of 12 members in the Patriot Program, a program designed to help protect vulnerable Republican incumbents heading into the 2016 election.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://atr.rollcall.com/nrcc-patriot-program-2016/|title=Exclusive: NRCC Announces 12 Members in Patriot Program|work=Roll Call: At the Races|accessdate=February 5, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Hohmann|first1=James|last2=Viebeck|first2=Elise|title=The Daily 202: Contract with the NRCC \u2014 The deal GOPers make to get reelected|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/powerpost/wp/2015/09/03/the-daily-202-contract-with-the-nrcc-the-deal-gopers-make-to-get-reelected|accessdate=February 5, 2016|work=The Washington Post|date=September 3, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2016 Republican primary, Zeldin faced no opposition. In the November 8 general election, he faced Democrat Anna Throne-Holst, a member of the [[Southampton, New York|Southampton]] Town Board.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Path\u00e9|first1=Simone|title=Throne-Holst Will Challenge New York's Lee Zeldin|url=http://www.rollcall.com/news/politics/democrats-new-york-house-zeldin-throne-holst-calone|accessdate=July 10, 2016|publisher=Roll Call|date=July 8, 2016}}</ref> Zeldin won with 58% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://suffolktimes.timesreview.com/2016/11/71661/live-results-zeldin-throne-holst-election-day-2016-ny-cd-1/|title=On night of Trump win, Zeldin makes history|publisher=|accessdate=November 10, 2016}}</ref> He became the only Jewish Republican in Congress, following Representative [[Eric Cantor]]\u2019s primary defeat.<ref name=autogenerated1 /><ref name=\"autogenerated8\">{{cite web|url=https://www.tabletmag.com/scroll/186851/meet-jewish-republican-congressman-lee-zeldin|title=Meet Lee Zeldin, Jewish Republican Congressman from New York|date=November 5, 2014|website=Tablet Magazine}}</ref>\n\n'''2018'''{{See also|2018 United States House of Representatives elections in New York#District 1}}\nZeldin ran unopposed in the 2018 Republican primary. In the November general election he faced Democratic nominee Perry Gershon and [[Working Families Party]] nominee Patricia Latzman.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.longislandadvance.net/5612/Perry-Gershon-to-face-Congressman-Lee-Zeldin-in-midterms|title=Perry Gershon to face Congressman Lee Zeldin in midterms|last=Smith|first=Tara|date=|work=|access-date=2018-09-11}}</ref> \n\nFor the second consecutive election, Zeldin's campaign sent voters mailers instructing them to postmark their absentee ballots by the wrong date, November 6; the actual deadline was November 5. Zeldin's Democratic opponent Perry Gershon's campaign said the mailers targeted likely Democratic voters, such as college students. Zeldin's campaign said the incorrect date was a mistake and provided a statement from its printer, PDQ Print and Mail, taking responsibility. The campaign said it sent a follow-up mailer with the correct date.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsday.com/long-island/politics/spin-cycle/zeldin-gershon-mailer-1.22304894|title=Zeldin mailer uses wrong deadline for absentees|publisher=|accessdate=November 23, 2018}}</ref> His campaign featured fundraisers with [[Sebastian Gorka]] and [[Breitbart News]] founder [[Steve Bannon]]. At one event, reporters from local news outlets were removed.<ref>{{cite web|url=pcli.org/2018/07/press-club-reacts-to-journalists-removal-from-rep-zeldins-political-rally|title=Press Club reacts to journalists' removal from Rep. Zeldin's political rally|publisher=|accessdate=July 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\nZeldin defeated Gershon 53%-47%.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.realclearpolitics.com/epolls/2018/house/ny/new_york_1st_district_zeldin_vs_gershon-6383.html|title=New York 1st District - Zeldin vs. Gershon|work=realclearpolitics.com|accessdate=December 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\n'''Committee assignments'''\n\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs|Committee on Foreign Affairs]]'''\n**[[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on the Middle East and North Africa|Subcommittee on the Middle East and North Africa]]\n**[[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on Terrorism, Nonproliferation, and Trade|Subcommittee on Terrorism, Nonproliferation, and Trade]]\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Financial Services|Committee on Financial Services]]'''\n**[[United States House Financial Services Subcommittee on Housing and Insurance|Subcommittee on Housing and Insurance]]\n**[[United States House Financial Services Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations|Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations]]\n**[[United States House Financial Services Subcommittee on Terrorism and Illicit Finance|Subcommittee on Terrorism and Illicit Finance]]\n\n'''Caucuses'''\n\nZeldin is a member of the [[Climate Solutions Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Climate Solutions Caucus|url=https://citizensclimatelobby.org/climate-solutions-caucus|website=Citizens Climate Lobby|accessdate=August 23, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Smith|first1=Tara|title=Citizens lobby for the environment|url=https://www.longislandadvance.net/4024/Citizens-lobby-for-the-environment|accessdate=September 6, 2017|publisher=The Long Island Advance|date=January 5, 2017}}</ref> and the [[Republican Main Street Partnership]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://republicanmainstreet.org/members/|format=|publisher=Republican Mains Street Partnership|date=|accessdate=4 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180826123025/https://republicanmainstreet.org/members/|archive-date=August 26, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> As of 2017 he was co-chair of the House Republican Israel Caucus.<ref>[https://www.jta.org/2017/06/01/politics/trump-signs-waiver-will-not-move-embassy-to-jerusalem \"Trump signs waiver, won\u2019t move embassy to Jerusalem now,\"] JTA, June 1, 2017.</ref>\n\n==Political positions==\nIn July 2015 Zeldin was among nine Republicans who faced criticism after meeting with [[Oath Keepers]], a group of retired military, police, and fire department employees. ''[[New York Daily News|The New York Daily News]]'' reported that \"the chapter's website includes postings by a member embracing a film that claims the December 2012 [[Sandy Hook Elementary School shooting|Sandy Hook massacre]] was a hoax, and calling President Obama a 'Muslim/Extremist.'\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/politics/rep-hit-meeting-extreme-conservatives-article-1.2281013|title=Long Island Rep. Lee Zeldin among nine Republicans facing attacks for meeting with extremist conservative group|work=New York Daily News}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2016 Zeldin was ranked as the 45th-most bipartisan member of the U.S. House of Representatives during the [[114th United States Congress]] (and the eighth-most-bipartisan member of the U.S. House of Representatives from New York) in the Bipartisan Index created by [[The Lugar Center]] and the [[McCourt School of Public Policy]] that ranks members of the United States Congress by their degree of bipartisanship (by measuring the frequency each member's bills attract co-sponsors from the opposite party, and each member's co-sponsorship of bills by members of the opposite party).<ref>{{Citation|title=The Lugar Center - McCourt School Bipartisan Index|date=March 7, 2016|url=http://www.thelugarcenter.org/assets/htmldocuments/The%20Lugar%20Center%20-%20McCourt%20School%20Bipartisan%20Index%20114th%20Congress%20House%20Scores.pdf|publisher=[[The Lugar Center]]|accessdate=April 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Education===\nIn July 2015 Zeldin attached an amendment to the [[Student Success Act]] to allow states to opt out of [[Common Core State Standards Initiative|Common Core]] without penalty.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.capitalnewyork.com/article/albany/2015/03/8563290/zeldin-begins-anti-common-core-amendment|title=Zeldin begins with an anti-Common Core amendment|accessdate=February 27, 2015|work=Politico New York}}</ref> The amendment was passed and signed into law.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://riverheadlocal.com/2015/12/03/education-bill-with-zeldin-amendment-to-allow-states-to-opt-out-of-common-core-passes-congress|title=Zeldin Anti-Common Core Amendment Passed|date=December 3, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Environment===\n\nIn April 2015, along with Senator [[Charles Schumer]], Zeldin introduced the Fluke Fairness Act. The bill would have changed the current system for managing [[Summer flounder|fluke]] fishing quotas by creating a regional approach to updating quotas and standards based on geographic, scientific, and economic data.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.riverheadlocal.com/2015/04/25/federal-fluke-fairness-act-would-correct-inequitable-treatment-of-l-i-anglers-schumer-zeldin|title=Federal 'Fluke Fairness Act' would correct inequitable treatment of L.I. anglers: Schumer, Zeldin|work=Riverhead Local}}</ref> The bill did not pass.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/114th-congress/senate-bill/1107|title=S.1107 - 114th Congress (2015-2016): Fluke Fairness Act of 2015|last=Charles|first=Schumer|date=2015-04-28|website=congress.gov|language=en|access-date=2018-09-22}}</ref>\n\nOn July 15, 2015, Zeldin introduced the [[Exclusive economic zone|Exclusive Economic Zone]] Clarification Act.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/114th-congress/house-bill/3070|title=H.R.3070|work=congress.gov|accessdate=March 3, 2016}}</ref> The bill proposed to amend the boundary in part of the federal [[Exclusive Economic Zone]] (EEZ). It would give fisheries management of [[Block Island Sound]] exclusively to New York and Rhode Island; some Connecticut fishermen said the bill could put them out of business.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wtnh.com/2016/02/15/proposed-bill-could-put-connecticut-fishermen-out-of-business|title=Bill in Congress could hurt Connecticut fishermen, and fish|accessdate=February 27, 2015|work=WTNH}}{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/wireStory/long-island-sound-discontent-fishing-rights-push-37220874|title=On Long Island Sound, Discord Over Push for Fishing Rights|accessdate=March 3, 2016|work=ABC News}}</ref> The bill died in committee.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/114th-congress/house-bill/3070/text|title=Text - H.R.3070 - 114th Congress (2015-2016): EEZ Transit Zone Clarification and Access Act|last=Lee|first=Zeldin|date=2016-06-08|website=congress.gov|language=en|access-date=2018-09-22}}</ref>\n\nAlso in September 2015, Zeldin, along with [[Citizens Campaign for the Environment]] executive director Adrienne Esposito, condemned a proposed federal plan for dumping of dredged materials, saying, \"We can't just assume that dumping these waste spoils in the [[Long Island Sound]] is environmentally benign.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Blasl|first1=Katie|title=Long Island Sound is 'not a landfill', say environmentalists opposed to open water waste dumping plan|url=http://www.riverheadlocal.com/2015/09/17/long-island-sound-is-not-a-landfill-say-environmentalists-opposed-to-open-water-waste-dumping-plan|accessdate=March 3, 2016|publisher=Riverhead Local|date=September 17, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Rep. Zeldin joins call to halt Sound dumping|url=http://longisland.news12.com/news/rep-zeldin-joins-call-to-halt-dredged-sediment-dumping-in-long-island-sound-1.10852637|accessdate=March 3, 2016|publisher=News12 LongIsland|date=September 16, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018 Zeldin said he did not support the [[Paris Agreement|Paris Accords]] in their form at that time. He expressed concern about \u201cother countries that are contributing to very adverse impacts on our climate but not having the level of responsibility that they need to have in stepping up and making a positive change in their own countries.\u201d<ref>[https://www.bloomberg.com/news/videos/2018-04-25/rep-zeldin-says-u-s-should-be-willing-to-decertify-iran-deal-video Rep. Zeldin Says U.S. Should Be Willing to Decertify Iran Deal] Bloomberg April 25, 2018</ref>\n\n===Foreign affairs===\nIn July 2016 Zeldin criticized [[Barack Obama|President Obama]]'s [[Iran nuclear deal framework|Iran Nuclear Deal]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newsday.com/long-island/lee-zeldin-steve-israel-reject-and-are-skeptical-of-iran-nuclear-deal-1.10640589|title=Republicans denounce Iran deal; Democrats respond cautiously|last1=Brune|first1=Tom|date=July 14, 2015|accessdate=June 20, 2016|publisher=Newsday}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2016 the ''[[New York Post]]'' reported that Zeldin was a no-show in 2015 at 12 of 18 [[United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs|House Committee on Foreign Affairs]] hearings that dealt specifically with [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|ISIL]] and with [[Syria]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2016/01/14/tough-talking-freshman-congressman-has-been-blowing-off-work|title=Tough-talking freshman congressman has been skipping Foreign Affairs Committee meetings|work=New York Post|accessdate=January 31, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsday.com/long-island/politics/spin-cycle/rep-lee-zeldin-s-hearing-absences-draw-fire-from-rivals-1.11347327?pts=474522|title=Rep. Lee Zeldin's hearing absences draw fire from rivals|work=Newsday|accessdate=January 31, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2016, along with Representatives [[Mike Pompeo]] of [[Kansas]] and [[Frank LoBiondo]] of [[New Jersey]], Zeldin sought visas to travel to [[Iran]] to check the country's compliance with the [[Iran nuclear deal framework]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Brune|first1=Tom|title=Rep. Lee Zeldin seeks Iran visa to check on nuke compliance|url=http://www.newsday.com/long-island/rep-lee-zeldin-seeks-iran-visa-to-check-on-nuke-compliance-1.11430362|accessdate=February 26, 2016|publisher=Newsday|date=February 4, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Nicholas|first1=Elizabeth|title=Meeting the Tea Party in Tehran|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/elizabeth-nicholas/meeting-the-tea-party-in-_b_9311336.html|accessdate=February 27, 2016|publisher=Huffington Post|date=February 25, 2016}}</ref> In June Iran called the request a \"publicity stunt\" and said it would deny the visas.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Vahdat|first1=Amir|title=Iran says US congressmen can't visit amid nuclear deal row|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/24bf91854009440cb610828c1d5a38dd/iran-says-us-congressmen-cant-visit-amid-nuclear-deal-row|accessdate=June 16, 2016|work=Associated Press|date=June 7, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Health care===\nIn May 2015 Zeldin voted for H.R.36, a bill he co-sponsored, which would prohibit abortions in cases where the probable age of the [[fetus]] is 20 weeks or later, and would impose criminal penalties on doctors who violate the ban.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsday.com/long-island/politics/spin-cycle/emily-s-list-declares-rep-zeldin-on-notice-for-2016-1.10496400|title=Emily's List Declares Rep Zeldin On Notice for 2016|work=Newsday}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015 Zeldin co-sponsored two bills in Congress to combat [[Lyme disease]], the Tick-Borne Disease Research and Accountability and Transparency Act of 2015<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/114th-congress/house-bill/789/cosponsors|title=H.R.789|work=congress.gov|accessdate=March 2, 2016}}</ref> and the [[21st Century Cures Act]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/114th-congress/house-bill/6/cosponsors|title=H.R.6|work=congress.gov|accessdate=March 2, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://suffolktimes.timesreview.com/2015/09/62315/grossman-column-time-to-legislate-against-lyme-disease|title=Grossman Column: Time to legislate against Lyme disease|date=September 20, 2015|publisher=The Suffolk Times|last1=Grossman|first1=Karl|accessdate=March 2, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn September 18, 2015, Zeldin voted for the Defund Planned Parenthood Act of 2015,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/114th-congress/house-bill/3134|title=H.R.3134|work=congress.gov|accessdate=March 2, 2016}}</ref> a bill that would defund [[Planned Parenthood]] for one year unless the organization agreed not to provide abortion services.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Harding|first1=Robert|title=HOW THEY VOTED: House passes bill to defund Planned Parenthood; Katko, Hanna split on vote|url=http://auburnpub.com/blogs/eye_on_ny/how-they-voted-house-passes-bill-to-defund-planned-parenthood/article_d48b67aa-5e25-11e5-917b-e3315121bff3.html|accessdate=March 2, 2016|publisher=The Citizen (Auburn New York)|date=September 19, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Merrill|first1=Kitty|title=Throne-Holst On The Offensive|url=http://www.indyeastend.com/Articles-News-i-2015-09-23-120005.113117-ThroneHolst-On-The-Offensive.html|accessdate=March 2, 2016|publisher=The Independent|date=September 23, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn May 4, 2017, Zeldin voted in favor of repealing the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]] (Obamacare) and passing the [[American Health Care Act of 2017|American Health Care Act]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.longislandadvance.net/4419/Zeldin-votes-to-repeal-Affordable-Care-Act|title=Zeldin votes to repeal Affordable Care Act|last1=Smith|first1=Tara|date=May 11, 2017|accessdate=May 15, 2017|publisher=Long Island Advance}}</ref><ref name=\":02\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/graphics/politics/ahca-house-vote|title=How the House voted to pass the GOP health-care bill|website=Washington Post|access-date=2017-05-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/05/04/politics/house-health-care-vote/index.html|title=How every member voted on health care bill|last=Staff|first=C.N.N.|website=CNN|accessdate=2017-05-04}}</ref>\n\n===Israel===\nZeldin has said that Israel is \u201cAmerica\u2019s strongest ally\" and that Congress must \u201cprotect Israel\u2019s right to self-defense.\u201d<ref name=\":5\" /> In 2016 he spoke in support of the anti-[[Boycott, Divestment and Sanctions]] (BDS) legislation that passed the [[New York State Senate]]. In March 2017 he co-sponsored a bipartisan bill in the House of Representatives, the Israel Anti-Boycott Act, to oppose boycotts of Israel and \u201cto further combat the anti-Israel boycott, divestment and sanctions (BDS) movement.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thetower.org/4773-bipartisan-bill-against-israel-boycotts-introduced-in-house-of-representatives/|title=Bipartisan Bill Against Israel Boycotts Introduced in House of Representatives|date=March 24, 2017|website=The Tower}}</ref>  He supported the Trump administration's decision to relocate the U.S. Embassy in Israel from Tel Aviv to Jerusalem in May 2018 as part of the [[United States recognition of Jerusalem as capital of Israel]].<ref>[http://www.27east.com/news/article.cfm/East-End/556348/Congressman-Lee-Zeldin-Attends-Opening-Of-US-Embassy-In-Israell Congressman Lee Zeldin Attends Opening Of U.S. Embassy In Israel]</ref>\n\n===Land management===\nIn April 2016 Zeldin introduced legislation to prevent the federal government's sale of [[Plum Island (New York)|Plum Island]] to the highest bidder.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Finn|first1=Lisa|title=Rep. Lee Zeldin on Battle to Preserve Plum Island: 'Losing's Not An Option'|url=http://patch.com/new-york/northfork/rep-lee-zeldin-battle-preserve-plum-island-losings-not-option|accessdate=April 28, 2016|publisher=North Fork Patch|date=April 24, 2016}}</ref> In May 2016 his bill unanimously passed the House.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Irizarry|first1=Lisa|title=Plum Island protection bill passed by House|url=http://www.newsday.com/long-island/suffolk/lee-zeldin-s-plum-island-bill-scheduled-for-house-vote-1.11802207|accessdate=May 17, 2016|publisher=Newsday|date=May 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== LGBT rights ===\n\nAs a New York state senator in 2011, Zeldin voted against the [[Marriage Equality Act (New York)|Marriage Equality Act]], which legalized same-sex marriage in the state.<ref>{{cite web |title=Assembly Bill A8354 |url=https://www.nysenate.gov/legislation/bills/2011/A8354 |website=The New York State Senate |accessdate=May 3, 2019}}</ref> In June 2015, after the [[Supreme Court of the United States|United States Supreme Court]] ruled in ''[[Obergefell v. Hodges]]'' that state-level bans on [[same-sex marriage]] were unconstitutional, Zeldin would not comment about his view of same-sex marriage, but indicated that he believed the issue should have been decided at the state level.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.27east.com/news/article.cfm/Water-Mill/112053/Supreme-Court-Ruling-Legalizes-Gay-Marriage-Bridgehampton-Ceremony-At-Center-Of-Case|title=Supreme Court Ruling Legalizes Gay Marriage; Bridgehampton Ceremony Was At Center Of Case|work=27east.com|accessdate=February 27, 2015}}</ref> A month later he signed on as a co-sponsor of the [[First Amendment Defense Act]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/114th-congress/house-bill/2802/cosponsors|title=HR 2802|work=congress.gov|accessdate=February 27, 2016}}</ref> a bill whose supporters said was designed to protect Americans who used their religious beliefs to deny services to same sex couples or unmarried pregnant women. Critics of the measure said it would enable people to violate the legal rights of same-sex couples and their children by discriminating against them.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lgbtweekly.com/2015/06/20/hrc-first-amendment-defense-act-is-reckless/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150725112902/http://lgbtweekly.com/2015/06/20/hrc-first-amendment-defense-act-is-reckless/|archivedate=2015-07-25|title=HRC: First Amendment Defense Act is 'reckless'|last1=Lee|first1=Steve|date=June 20, 2015|publisher=San Diego LGBT Weekly (San Diego California)|accessdate=October 25, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/first-amendment-defense-act_55a7ffe6e4b04740a3df4ca1|title=First Amendment Defense Act|work=huffingtonpost.com|accessdate=October 25, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://dyn.realclearpolitics.com/congressional_bill_tracker/bill/114/hr2802|title=H.R. 2802: First Amendment Defense Act|work=RealClearPolitics.com|accessdate=March 2, 2016}}</ref> In May 2019, Zeldin voted against the [[Equality Act (United States)|Equality Act]].<ref>[https://www.congress.gov/bill/116th-congress/house-bill/5 H.R. 5]</ref><ref>[http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2019/roll217.xml|FINAL VOTE RESULTS FOR ROLL CALL 217]</ref><ref>[https://thinkprogress.org/25-equality-act-opponents-from-states-with-lgbtq-non-discrimination-protections-8fba0c05e4f7/ These 25 Republicans should have known better about the Equality Act]</ref>\n\n=== Taxes ===\n\nIn November 2017 Zeldin said he was not yet satisfied with the proposed Republican tax bill. He complained in particular about the elimination of the state and local tax deduction. That same month House Speaker [[Paul D. Ryan]] canceled plans to attend a fundraiser for Zeldin after Zeldin voted against the House version of the bill.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/29/nyregion/ryan-fundraiser-zeldin-tax-bill.html|title=Paul Ryan Cancels Fund-Raiser for Lee Zeldin Over Tax Bill Vote|last=Goldmacher|first=Shane|date=November 29, 2017|work=New York Times|access-date=September 5, 2018|language=en}}</ref> In December Zeldin called the tax bill \u201ca geographic redistribution of wealth\u201d that takes money from some states while providing [[tax relief]] to others. He suggested that the removal of the [[state tax]] deduction could have been implemented gradually.<ref>[https://www.npr.org/2017/11/03/561781225/republican-rep-lee-zeldin-on-his-opposition-to-gop-tax-bill?t=1533140083378 Republican Rep. Lee Zeldin On His Opposition To GOP Tax Bill] NPR November 3, 2017</ref><ref>[https://www.cnbc.com/2017/12/20/gop-rep-lee-zeldin-tax-bill-a-geographic-redistribution-of-wealth.html GOP congressman votes 'no' on tax bill, calls it a 'geographic redistribution of wealth'] Michelle Fox; CNBC; December 20, 2017</ref>\n\nZeldin voted against the [[Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017]], which passed in December 2017.<ref name=\"Almukhtar122117\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/12/19/us/politics/tax-bill-house-live-vote.html?_r=0|title=How Each House Member Voted on the Tax Bill|last1=Almukhtar|first1=Sarah|date=19 December 2017|website=The New York Times|accessdate=21 December 2017}}</ref> He supported the [[corporate tax]] cuts in the bill but did not approve of the limit for [[property tax]] deductions, preferring a cap of $20,000 or $25,000 as opposed to the $10,000 that was in the bill.<ref name=\"yahoo122117\">{{cite web|url=https://uk.finance.yahoo.com/news/gop-congressman-votes-apos-no-201200326.html|title=GOP congressman votes 'no' on tax bill, calls it a 'geographic redistribution of wealth'|website=Yahoo! Finance|accessdate=21 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Trump administration ===\nOn May 3, 2016, Zeldin endorsed [[Donald Trump]] as the Republican presidential nominee.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Brune|first1=Tom|title=Reps. Peter King, Lee Zeldin endorse Donald Trump for president|url=http://www.newsday.com/long-island/politics/spin-cycle/reps-peter-king-lee-zeldin-endorse-donald-trump-for-president-1.11762295|accessdate=August 15, 2016|publisher=Newsday|date=May 4, 2016}}</ref> Zeldin had previously indicated that he would support the eventual Republican nominee.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Clancy|first1=Ambrose|title=Zeldin will support whoever GOP nominates|url=http://suffolktimes.timesreview.com/2016/03/66217/zeldin-will-support-republican-presidential-nominee-even-trump|accessdate=August 15, 2016|publisher=Suffolk Times|date=March 3, 2016}}</ref> During the campaign, Zeldin faulted Trump for a comment about [[Khizr and Ghazala Khan]], a [[Gold Star family]] whose son Humayun, a [[Captain (United States)|Captain]] in the [[United States Army|Army]], was killed during the [[Iraq War]], but stated he would continue to support Trump.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Brune|first1=Tom|title=Peter King, Lee Zeldin fault Donald Trump for dispute with Khans|url=http://www.newsday.com/long-island/politics/spin-cycle/peter-king-lee-zeldin-fault-donald-trump-for-dispute-with-khans-1.12125170?pts=787531|publisher=Newsday|date=August 2, 2016|accessdate=August 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017 Zeldin supported Trump's [[Dismissal of James Comey|firing of FBI Director James Comey]], saying it offered the [[FBI]] a chance at a \"fresh start\" to rebuild trust.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.newsday.com/long-island/politics/comey-s-firing-spurs-call-for-russia-probe-special-prosecutor-1.13589403|title=With Comey out, Schumer urges special prosecutor|work=Newsday|access-date=2017-05-10}}</ref> In May 2018 Zeldin called for the criminal prosecution of former FBI deputy director [[Andrew McCabe]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/389036-watch-ny-republican-wants-mccabe-prosecuted|title=WATCH: NY Republican wants McCabe prosecuted|last=Hooper|first=Molly K.|date=2018-05-23|work=TheHill|access-date=2018-05-23|language=en}}</ref> Also that month Zeldin called for creating a [[special counsel]] investigation into the FBI and the [[United States Department of Justice|DOJ]] regarding their investigations into [[Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/policy/national-security/388798-house-conservatives-introduce-resolution-calling-for-second-special|title=House conservatives introduce resolution calling for second special counsel|last=Beavers|first=Olivia|date=2018-05-22|work=TheHill|access-date=2018-05-23|language=en}}</ref> Zeldin said the investigations were launched with \"insufficient intelligence and biased motivations\", with surveillance warrants for Trump campaign staffers obtained in \"deeply flawed and questionable\" ways.<ref name=\":1\" /> He also called for an investigation into the FBI's decision to conclude its investigation into the [[Hillary Clinton email controversy]].<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2018/05/22/politics/republicans-house-second-special-counsel-proposal/index.html|title=Republicans renew push for second special counsel|author1=Jeremy Herb |author2=Daniella Diaz|work=CNN|access-date=2018-05-23}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2018\u201319 United States federal government shutdown]] Zeldin voted with the Republican caucus against the controversial appropriations measure to fund the federal government. He instructed the House to withhold his pay until the shutdown ended, saying: \u201cIt\u2019s crazy to me that members of Congress get paid while other federal employees do not.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|last=Civiletti|first=Denise|url=https://riverheadlocal.com/2019/01/04/in-the-new-minority-rep-lee-zeldins-first-day-of-his-third-term-in-congress/|title=In the new minority: Rep. Lee Zeldin's first day of his third term in Congress|work=riverheadlocal.com|date= January 4, 2019|accessdate=January 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\nZeldin defended Trump amid the [[Trump\u2013Ukraine scandal]], which set off an impeachment inquiry against Trump over his request that Ukrainian President [[Volodymyr Zelensky]] investigate Democratic presidential candidate Joe Biden and his son Hunter Biden. Zeldin said in October 2019, \"It is crystal clear... that any allegation that President Trump was trying to get President Zelensky to manufacture dirt on the Bidens is just not true\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afp.com/en/news/15/intel-official-testify-new-texts-pile-pressure-trump-doc-1l13hu5|title=Intel official to testify as new texts pile pressure on Trump|website=AFP.com|language=en|access-date=2019-10-04}}</ref>\n\nZeldin has become one of Trump's staunchest defenders during his public impeachment hearings. In the seven impeachment deposition transcripts released so far, no Republican has spoken more than Zeldin, who is referenced more than 550 times.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/trump-impeachment-inquiry/trump-s-defender-how-little-known-gop-lawmaker-became-point-n1076046|title=How a little-known GOP lawmaker became a point man in Trump's impeachment defense|website=NBC News|language=en|access-date=2019-11-11}}</ref>\n\n===Veterans affairs===\nIn February 2015 Zeldin introduced his first bill, to eliminate the dollar limit for loans that the [[United States Department of Veterans Affairs]] can guarantee for a veteran.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newsday.com/long-island/politics/spin-cycle/rice-and-zeldin-file-first-bills-aimed-at-aiding-vets-1.10068978|title=Rice, Zeldin file first bills aimed at aiding vets|accessdate=February 5, 2016|publisher=Newsday}}</ref> In February 2016 he proposed federal legislation to fund a three-year, $25-million nationwide veterans' peer-support program modeled on one he helped establish while a member of the New York State Senate.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newsday.com/long-island/politics/lee-zeldin-proposes-25m-veterans-counseling-program-1.11469897|title=Lee Zeldin proposes $25M veterans counseling program|last1=Evans|first1=Martin|date=February 14, 2016|accessdate=February 26, 2016|publisher=Newsday}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nZeldin is Jewish,<ref name=\"Printing2016\">{{cite book|author=Congress (U S ) Joint Committee on Printing|title=Official Congressional Directory 114th Congress, 2015-2016, Convened January 2015|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=W4Som-OxRt4C&pg=PA180|date=30 March 2016|publisher=Government Printing Office|isbn=978-0-16-092997-7|pages=180\u2013}}</ref> and his wife, Diana, is Mormon.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ain|first1=Stewart|title=L.I.'s Zeldin Stepping Into GOP Minefield|url=http://jewishweek.timesofisrael.com/l-i-s-zeldin-stepping-into-gop-minefield|accessdate=July 5, 2018|publisher=The New York Jewish Week|date=November 12, 2014}}</ref> The couple has identical twin daughters, Mikayla and Arianna.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gonzales|first1=Nathan|title=Washington Is a Matter of Life and Death to Congressional Candidate|url=https://www.rollcall.com/news/washington-is-a-matter-of-life-and-death-to-congressional-candidate|accessdate=February 26, 2016|publisher=Roll Call|date=January 24, 2014}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated1 /> They live in [[Shirley, New York]].<ref name=\"Official bio\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Jewish members of the United States Congress]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{commonscat}}\n* [https://zeldin.house.gov/ Congressman Lee Zeldin] official U.S. House site\n* [https://zeldinforcongress.com// Zeldin for Congress] official campaign site\n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/New_York/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Lee_Zeldin_%5BR-1%5D}}\n{{ CongLinks | congbio = Z000017 | fec = H8NY01148 | votesmart = 110252| congress = lee-zeldin/Z000017}}\t\t\n* {{C-SPAN|leezeldin}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-ny-sen}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Brian X. Foley]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[New York State Senate|New York Senate]]<br>from the 3rd district|years=2011\u20132013}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Thomas Croci]]}}\n|-\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{US House succession box\n|before   = [[Tim Bishop]]\n|state    = New York\n|district = 1\n|years    = 2015\u2013present}}\n|-\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Bruce Westerman]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Seniority in the United States House of Representatives|United States Representatives by seniority]]|years=279th}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Trent Kelly]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{USCongRep-start|congresses= 114th-116th [[United States Congress]] |state=[[United States congressional delegations from New York|New York]]}}\n{{USCongRep/NY/114}}\n{{USCongRep/NY/115}}\n{{USCongRep/NY/116}}\n{{USCongRep-end}}\n{{NY-FedRep}}\n{{USHouseCurrent}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zeldin, Lee}}\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Albany Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Jewish American military personnel]]\n[[Category:American army personnel of the Iraq War]]\n[[Category:Jewish members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Republicans]]\n[[Category:New York (state) lawyers]]\n[[Category:New York state senators]]\n[[Category:People from Shirley, New York]]\n[[Category:Republican Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:United States Army officers]]\n", "name_user": "1990'sguy", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eElections:Dash.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lee_Zeldin"}
